wiki_description: The Saint-Denis Basilica of Saint-Denis is a Gothic style church located in the center of the city of Saint-Denis.

The Ensérune oppidum is an archaeological site comprising the remains of an ancient village, located on a hill in the commune of Nissan-lez-Enserune, in the department of Hérault (France). This village was occupied between the 6th century BC. BC (Iron Age) and the 1st century AD. Its position at the top of a hill earned it the title of oppidum.

The Château d'Assier is located in Assier, in the Lot department of the Occitanie region of south-west France. It is an example of the diffusion of Renaissance château architecture from the Loire Valley into other parts of France.

The Cathedral of Saint Lazarus of Autun (French: Cathédrale Saint-Lazare d'Autun), commonly known as Autun Cathedral, is a Roman Catholic cathedral in Autun and a national monument of France. Famous for its Cluniac inspiration and its Romanesque sculptures by Gislebertus, it is a highlight of Romanesque art in Burgundy. It is the seat of the Roman Catholic Diocese of Autun and its Bishop. The Bishop of Autun set forth the construction of St. Lazarus Cathedral as a result of the large movement of pilgrims travelling to Vezelay as they progressed on the pilgrimage route to Santiago de Compostela.

The Château d'Angers is a castle in the city of Angers in the Loire Valley, in the département of Maine-et-Loire, in France. Founded in the 9th century by the Counts of Anjou, it was expanded to its current size in the 13th century. It is located overhanging the River Maine. It is a listed historical monument since 1875. Now open to the public, the Château d'Angers is home of the Apocalypse Tapestry.

The Column of the Grande Armée (French - Colonne de la grande Armée or Colonne Napoléone) is a 53 metre high Corinthian order triumphal column (modelled on Trajan's Column and other triumphal columns in Rome) on the Rue Napoleon in Wimille, near Boulogne-sur-Mer, France.
The royal monastery of Brou is a religious complex located in Bourg-en-Bresse in the Ain department, in the Auvergne-Rhône-Alpes region.

The Carnac stones (Breton: Steudadoù Karnag) are an exceptionally dense collection of megalithic sites near the south coast of Brittany in northwestern France, consisting of stone alignments (rows), dolmens (stone tombs), tumuli (burial mounds) and single menhirs. More than 3,000 prehistoric standing stones were hewn from local granite and erected by the pre-Celtic people of Brittany and form the largest such collection in the world. Most of the stones are within the Breton municipality of Carnac, but some to the east are within neighboring La Trinité-sur-Mer. The stones were erected at some stage during the Neolithic period, probably around 3300 BC, but some may date to as early as 4500 BC.

The Cairn of Barnenez (also: Barnenez Tumulus, Barnenez Mound; in Breton Karn Barnenez; in French: Cairn de Barnenez or Tumulus de Barnenez) is a Neolithic monument located near Plouezoc'h, on the Kernéléhen peninsula in northern Finistère, Brittany, France. It dates to the early Neolithic, around 4000 BC. Along with the Tumulus of Bougon and Locmariaquer megaliths, also located in Great West France, it is one of the earliest megalithic monuments in Europe and one of the oldest man-made structures in the world. It is also remarkable for the presence of megalithic art.
The Mont-Dauphin fort is a fortified complex, part of the Vauban fortifications listed by UNESCO, and classified as a historic monument.

input_name: Château et remparts de la Cité de Carcassonne
wiki_description: The City of Carcassonne is a medieval architectural ensemble located in the French city of Carcassonne in the Aude department, Occitanie region. It is located on the right bank of the Aude, southeast of the current city. This fortified medieval city, whose origins date back to the Gallo-Roman period, owes its fame to its double enclosure, reaching almost 3 km in length and comprising fifty-two towers, which dominates the Aude valley. The City also includes a castle (the count’s castle) and a basilica (the Saint-Nazaire basilica).

The Château de Vincennes (French pronunciation: ) is a former fortress and royal residence next to the town of Vincennes, on the eastern edge of Paris, alongside the Bois de Vincennes. It was largely built between 1361 and 1369, and was a preferred residence, after the Palais de la Cité, of French kings from the 14th to 16th century. It is particularly known for its "donjon" or keep, a fortified central tower (the tallest in Europe) built in the 14th century and for the chapel, Sainte-Chapelle de Vincennes, begun in 1379 but not completed until 1552, which is an exceptional example of Flamboyant Gothic architecture. Because of its fortifications, the château was often used as a royal sanctuary in times of trouble and as a prison and military headquarters. The chapel was listed as an historic monument in 1853 and the keep was listed in 1913. Most of the building is now open to the public.
The Tour Pey-Berland (Pey Berland Tower), named for its patron Pey Berland, is the separate bell tower of the Bordeaux Cathedral, in Bordeaux at the Place Pey Berland.

The Hôtel de Sully (French pronunciation: ) is a Louis XIII style hôtel particulier, or private mansion, located at 62 Rue Saint-Antoine in the Marais, 4th arrondissement, Paris, France. Built at the beginning of the 17th century, it is nowadays the seat of the Centre des monuments nationaux, the French national organization responsible for national heritage sites. It has been listed since 1862 as a monument historique by the Ministry of Culture.
The Hôtel de Sade is a building in Avignon, in the Vaucluse department.

The Chapel of the Moines is a Romanesque chapel integrated into a deanery called the Château des Moines located on the territory of the commune of Berzé-la-Ville in the French department of Saône-et-Loire in the Burgundy-Franche-Comté region.

The Château de Bussy-Rabutin, also known as Château de Bussy-le-Grand, is a château which developed from a 12th-century castle, located in the commune of Bussy-le-Grand, in the Côte-d'Or department, Bourgogne, eastern France.

The Château de Bouges (French pronunciation: ) is an 18th-century mansion in the town of Bouges-le-Château, in the Indre département of France, in the Loire Valley. It is classified as a monument historique and the gardens are listed by the Ministry of Culture as among the Notable Gardens of France. The château and gardens are open to the public.

The July Column (French: Colonne de Juillet, ) is a monumental column in Paris commemorating the Revolution of 1830. It stands in the center of the Place de la Bastille and celebrates the Trois Glorieuses — the 'three glorious' days of 27–29 July 1830 that saw the fall of Charles X, King of France, and the commencement of the July Monarchy of Louis-Philippe, King of the French. It was built between 1835 and 1840.

The Conciergerie (French pronunciation: ) (English: Lodge) is a former courthouse and prison in Paris, France located on the west of the Île de la Cité below the Palais de Justice. It was originally part of the former royal palace, the Palais de la Cité, which also included the Sainte-Chapelle. Two large medieval halls remain from the royal palace. During the French Revolution, 2,781 prisoners, including Marie Antoinette, were imprisoned, tried and sentenced at the Conciergerie then sent to different sites to be executed by the guillotine. It’s now a national monument and museum.

The Cathedral of Our Lady of Amiens (French: Cathédrale Notre-Dame d'Amiens), or simply Amiens Cathedral, is a Catholic cathedral. The cathedral is the seat of the Bishop of Amiens. It is situated on a slight ridge overlooking the River Somme in Amiens, the administrative capital of the Picardy region of France, some 120 kilometres (75 miles) north of Paris.

The Château d'Azay-le-Rideau (pronounced ) is located in the town of Azay-le-Rideau in the French département of Indre-et-Loire. Built between 1518 and 1527, this château is considered one of the foremost examples of early French renaissance architecture. Set on an island in the middle of the Indre river, this picturesque château has become one of the most popular of the châteaux of the Loire valley.

The Château de Maisons (now Château de Maisons-Laffitte ), designed by François Mansart from 1630 to 1651, is a prime example of French Baroque architecture and a reference point in the history of French architecture. The château is located in Maisons-Laffitte, a northwestern suburb of Paris, in the department of Yvelines, Île-de-France.

Montmajour Abbey, formally the Abbey of St. Peter in Montmajour (French: Abbaye Saint-Pierre de Montmajour ; Occitan: Abadia de Sancte Pèire en Montmajour), was a fortified Benedictine monastery built between the 10th and 18th centuries on what was originally an island five kilometers north of Arles, in what is now the Bouches-du-Rhône Department, in the region of Provence in the south of France.

Thoronet Abbey (French: L'abbaye du Thoronet) is a former Cistercian abbey built in the late twelfth and early thirteenth century, now restored as a museum. It is sited between the towns of Draguignan and Brignoles in the Var Department of Provence, in southeast France. It is one of the three Cistercian abbeys in Provence, along with the Sénanque Abbey and Silvacane, that together are known as "the Three Sisters of Provence."

The Panthéon (French:  ⓘ, from Ancient Greek πάνθειον (pántheion) ' to all the gods') is a monument in the 5th arrondissement of Paris, France. It stands in the Latin Quarter (Quartier Latin), on the Montagne Sainte-Geneviève, in the centre of the Place du Panthéon, which was named after it. The edifice was built between 1758 and 1790, from designs by Jacques-Germain Soufflot, at the behest of King Louis XV; the king intended it as a church dedicated to Saint Genevieve, Paris's patron saint, whose relics were to be housed in the church. Neither Soufflot nor Louis XV lived to see the church completed.
The Château de Châteaudun is a castle located in the town of Châteaudun in the French department of Eure-et-Loir.

Villa Savoye (French pronunciation: ) is a modernist villa and gatelodge in Poissy, on the outskirts of Paris, France. It was designed by the Swiss-French architect Le Corbusier and his cousin Pierre Jeanneret, and built between 1928 and 1931 using reinforced concrete.
The Château de Fougères-sur-Bièvre is a castle in the commune of Fougères-sur-Bièvre, in the French department of Loir-et-Cher.
Puyguilhem Castle may refer to two French castles in the Dordogne:

The Château d'If (French pronunciation: ; Occitan: Castèl d'If) is a fortress located on the Île d'If (Ilha d'If), the smallest island in the Frioul archipelago, situated about 1.5 kilometres (7⁄8 mile) offshore from Marseille in southeastern France. Built in the 16th century, it later served as a prison until the end of the 19th century. The fortress was demilitarized and opened to the public in 1890. It is famous for being one of the settings of Alexandre Dumas's adventure novel The Count of Monte Cristo. It is one of the most visited sites in the city of Marseille (nearly 100,000 visitors per year).
La Rochelle Listenⓘ is a French commune, prefecture of the Charente-Maritime department, in the Nouvelle-Aquitaine region.

The Château de Montal is a French Renaissance château located in the heart of the valley of the Bave in the commune of Saint-Jean-Lespinasse in Lot department in the region of Occitanie, in southwestern France. The château has been classified as a historical monuments since 14 June 1909.
The Château de Pierrefonds (French pronunciation: ) is a castle situated in the commune of Pierrefonds in the Oise department in the Hauts-de-France region, Northern France.
Villa Cavrois in Croix is a large modernist mansion built in 1932 by French architect Robert Mallet-Stevens for Paul Cavrois, an industrialist from Roubaix active in the textile industry.

input_name: Cité internationale de la langue française - château de Villers-Cotterêts
wiki_name: Cité internationale de la langue française
wiki_description: The Cité internationale de la langue française (sometimes abbreviated CILF) is a cultural place entirely dedicated to the French language and French-speaking cultures. It took place at the Château de Villers-Cotterêts, in the Aisne department, in the Hauts-de-France region. This castle is the very place where King François I signed the ordinance of 1539 making the use of French obligatory in administrative and judicial acts in France.

input_name: Maison et jardins de Georges Clemenceau
wiki_description: The house and gardens of Georges Clemenceau is a country house-beach house in Vendée, on the edge of the Atlantic Ocean, at a place called “Bélesbat” (renamed Belébat) in Saint-Vincent-sur-Jard in Vendée (Pays de la Loire). Famous for having belonged to the politician Georges Clemenceau during the last ten years of his life, from 1919 to 1929, this house museum and its gardens have been classified as historic monuments since July 10, 1970, and labeled Maisons des Illustres since 2011.

The Château de Castelnau-Bretenoux (French pronunciation: ) is a castle in the commune of Prudhomat, Lot département, France. One of the most impressive in the Quercy region, it has been listed as a monument historique by the French Ministry of Culture since 1862.
The Saorge Monastery is a former Catholic monastery located in Saorge, France.

The Chapelle expiatoire (French pronunciation: , "Expiatory Chapel") is a Roman Catholic chapel located in the 8th arrondissement of Paris, France. The chapel was constructed by Louis XVIII on the grounds where King Louis XVI and Queen Marie Antoinette had been buried after they had been guillotined, and it is dedicated to them as an expiation for that act. The remains of Louis XVI and Marie Antoinette are not in the chapel; they are in the Basilica of Saint-Denis, near Paris, with other French monarchs.

The Palais Jacques Cœur is a large hôtel particulier built by Jacques Cœur for himself and his family in Bourges, France. Built and decorated in the flamboyant style, it is widely viewed as one of the most prominent examples of French civilian architecture in the 15th century.

The cloister of the Saint-Gatien cathedral of Tours, or Psalette cloister, is located in the Saint-Gatien district of Vieux-Tours. It is managed by the Center des monuments nationaux. It has been classified as a historic monument since 1889.

The Château de Champs-sur-Marne (French pronunciation: ) is a neoclassical château in Champs-sur-Marne, France. It was built in its present form for the treasurer Charles Renouard de la Touane in 1699 by Pierre Bullet, architecte du roi. After the first proprietor's bankruptcy, another financier, Paul Poisson de Bourvalais, took up the project. Jean-Baptiste Bullet de Chamblain, the son of Pierre Bullet, finished Champs in 1706.

Villeneuve-Lembron Castle is a castle located in Villeneuve between Clermont-Ferrand and Saint-Flour, in the Puy-de-Dôme department in France. Managed on behalf of the State by the Center for National Monuments, it is renowned for the interest of its painted decorations.

The Château d'Oiron is located in Oiron, in the Deux-Sèvres département of western France. It has its origins in the 15th century war with the English for control of France when a victorious Charles VII of France gave the domain and great forest of Oiron to Guillaume Gouffier who became governor of Touraine. This château is the background for Charles Perrault's fairy tale, Puss in Boots. King Louis XIV's mistress, Madame de Montespan was one of the residents in the place.

The Locmariaquer megalith site is a megalithic complex located in Locmariaquer and managed by the Center des monuments nationaux. The site presents three megaliths illustrating the diversity of Neolithic constructions in Morbihan built between -5000 and -3800 years ago: the large broken menhir of Er Grah, the tumulus of Er Grah, the Marchand table.

Cluny Abbey (French: ; French: Abbaye de Cluny, formerly also Cluni or Clugny; Latin: Abbatia Cluniacensis) is a former Benedictine monastery in Cluny, Saône-et-Loire, France. It was dedicated to Saints Peter and Paul.

Notre-Dame Cathedral in Puy-en-Velay is a major monument of Romanesque art and Western Christianity. It was erected as a minor basilica by an apostolic brief from Pius IX on February 11, 1856. Its full title is Notre-Dame-de-l'Annonciation du Puy-en-Velay.

input_name: Sites préhistoriques de la vallée de la Vézère
wiki_name: Sites préhistoriques et grottes ornées de la vallée de la Vézère
wiki_description: The prehistoric sites and decorated caves of the Vézère valley constitute a set of exceptional prehistoric sites, spread over around forty kilometers along the Vézère valley between Les Eyzies-de-Tayac and Montignac, in Dordogne, Nouvelle-Aquitaine region, in France.
The George Sand estate - often referred to simply as George Sand's house or Nohant castle - is an 18th century castle, located in Nohant-Vic, about thirty kilometers from Châteauroux.

The Sainte-Chapelle (French: ; English: Holy Chapel) is a royal chapel in the Gothic style, within the medieval Palais de la Cité, the residence of the Kings of France until the 14th century, on the Île de la Cité in the River Seine in Paris, France.

input_name: Tours de la cathédrale de Reims
wiki_description: Notre-Dame de Reims Cathedral is a Roman Catholic cathedral located in Reims, in the French department of Marne in the Grand Est region. It is known to have been, from the 11th century, the place of almost all the coronations of the kings of France.

Cadillac Castle is located in the commune of Cadillac, in the French department of Gironde. The castle, the moat and the garden are classified as historic monuments by the 1862 list and by decree of July 12, 1956; the door to the vegetable garden was listed as a historic monument in 1965.

input_name: Cloître de la cathédrale de Bayonne
wiki_description: Sainte-Marie Cathedral or Notre-Dame de Bayonne is a Latin rite Catholic cathedral located in the Pyrénées-Atlantiques department (southwest of France). Built in the 13th and 14th centuries, it is characteristic of the Gothic style. It is the episcopal seat of the diocese of Bayonne.

Château de La Motte-Tilly is a castle in the commune of La Motte-Tilly, 7 kilometres (4 mi) south-west of Nogent-sur-Seine, Aube, France. It is on the left bank of the Seine and has been open to the public since 1978. The château is managed by the Centre des monuments nationaux.

Notre-Dame du Bec Abbey is a Benedictine Catholic abbey, today part of the congregation of Sainte-Marie du Mont-Olivet and located in Bec-Hellouin, near Brionne, in the Eure department, in Normandy. It was founded in 1034 by Herluin, or Helloin, hence its name, knight of Count Gilbert de Brionne.

The Notre-Dame de Beaulieu-en-Rouergue (or Belloc) abbey is a former Cistercian abbey founded in 1144 and which is today a center of contemporary art. It is located in the commune of Ginals in the north-east of the department of Tarn-et-Garonne on the border of the departments of Tarn and Aveyron. Beaulieu-en-Rouergue Abbey, like a hundred other monuments, property of the State, is managed, animated and open to visitors by the Center of National Monuments.
The ramparts of Aigues-Mortes are a masonry enclosure protecting the town center of Aigues-Mortes, in the Gard department, in the Occitanie region.

input_name: Trésor de la cathédrale de Lyon
wiki_description: The Saint-Jean-Baptiste-et-Saint-Étienne primatial church (also known, more simply, as Saint-Jean Cathedral) is the episcopal seat of the archdiocese of Lyon. It has the rank of cathedral and primatial: the archbishop of Lyon has the title of primate of Gaul.

The Astronomical Clock of Saint-Jean Cathedral in Besançon is an astronomical clock considered a masterpiece of its kind, built by Auguste-Lucien Vérité in the 19th century. It follows the astronomical clock of Constant Flavien Bernardin, built around 1850-1855, with complicated and defective functioning, which disappeared (or was integrated into that of Vérité) around 1860.
Montcaret is a French commune located in the Dordogne department, in the Nouvelle-Aquitaine region.

The Château des Beauvau-Craon, known as Château d'Haroué, is an 18th century castle located in a small valley in the center of the commune of Haroué, in Saintois, south of Nancy (department of Meurthe-et-Moselle).

The Hôtel de la Marine (French pronunciation: ), also known (formerly) as the Hôtel du Garde-Meuble (), is an historic building on the Place de la Concorde in Paris, just east of Rue Royale. It was designed by the architect Ange-Jacques Gabriel and built between 1757 and 1774 on the newly created square first called Place Louis XV. The identical building across the street, constructed at the same time, now houses the Hôtel de Crillon and the Automobile Club of France.

The Salses Fortress is a military structure built between 1497 and 1503 by the Spanish Catholic kings, Ferdinand II of Aragon and Isabella of Castile. It is located in the town of Salses-le-Château, 17 km north of Perpignan, in the Pyrénées-Orientales department.

The Château de Talcy is a historical building in Talcy, Loir-et-Cher, France. It lies to the north of the river Loire, in the Loire Valley, known for its 16th-century châteaux. From a fortification in existence in the 13th century additional wings were added in the 1620s. Modernised in the 18th century the interiors have been preserved. A Historical Monument first registered in 1906 it has been owned by the state since 1933. It is open to visitors.

input_name: Crypte et tour de la cathédrale de Bourges
wiki_description: Saint-Étienne de Bourges Cathedral is a Catholic cathedral built between the end of the 12th and the end of the 13th century. Dedicated to Saint Stephen, the first martyr, it is the seat of the archdiocese of Bourges (departments of Cher and Indre).

input_name: Sites et musée archéologiques de Montmaurin
wiki_description: The Arc de Triomphe de l'Étoile, most often called simply the Arc de Triomphe, is a tetrapyl-type monument located in Paris, at a high point at the junction of the territories of the 8th, 16th and 17th arrondissements, notably at the top of the avenue des Champs-Élysées and the avenue de la Grande-Armée, which constitute a major east-west Parisian axis starting from the Louvre pyramid, passing through the obelisk of La Concorde, the Arc de Triomphe itself and ending in the distance with the Arch of La Défense. Its construction, decided by Emperor Napoleon I, began in 1806 and was completed in 1836 under the reign of Louis-Philippe.
Glanum is an ancient city of the Roman Empire, today an archaeological site located in the territory of the commune of Saint-Rémy-de-Provence, in Bouches-du-Rhône.
The Château de Chareil-Cintrat, also known as the Château du Bas-Chareil, is a late medieval château in France. It is located near Chareil-Cintrat, in the Allier department, Auvergne.

Grande-Sauve Abbey or Sauve-Majeure Abbey is a former Benedictine monastery near the present village of La Sauve in the France department of the Gironde, in a region once heavily forested. Although now in ruins, the remains of the abbey are still of great interest in terms of Romanesque architecture, especially because of the many sculpted capitals still surviving.
The Fort Saint-André is a medieval fortress in the commune of Villeneuve-lès-Avignon in the Gard département of France, dating from the first half of the 14th century.

The Ernest-Renan museum is located at 20 rue Ernest-Renan in Tréguier, in the French department of Côtes-d'Armor. Dedicated to the Breton writer and philosopher Ernest Renan, it is installed in his birthplace.

Notre-Dame de Chartres Cathedral is a Catholic building located in the heart of the city of Chartres in the French department of Eure-et-Loir, in the Centre-Val de Loire region. A monument of Gothic architecture, it is traditionally considered one of the best preserved cathedrals of this style due to its sculptures, stained glass windows and paving.
The Pair-non-Pair cave is an ornate cave, discovered in 1881, which contains artistic representations dated more than 32,000 years before the present, attributed to the Aurignacian culture.

input_name: Domaine national du château de Coucy
wiki_description: Coucy Castle is a former fortified castle and stately residence, built from the 13th century, today in ruins and whose remains stand in the French commune of Coucy-le-Château-Auffrique in the Aisne department, in the Hauts-de-France region. The castle was the seat of the powerful House of Coucy until the death of Enguerrand VII of Coucy in 1397.

The Parc de Saint-Cloud (pronounced ; Park of Saint-Cloud), officially the Domaine national de Saint-Cloud (pronounced ; National Estate of Saint-Cloud), is a domaine national (national estate) located mostly within the Saint-Cloud commune, in the Hauts-de-Seine department, southwest of Paris, France.

input_name: Cloître de la cathédrale de Fréjus
wiki_description: Saint-Léonce de Fréjus Cathedral is a Catholic cathedral located in the historic center of Fréjus, in the Var department. It has been classified as a Historic Monument since 1862. It is a building of medieval origin but resulting from several eras:

The Mont-Saint-Michel Abbey is a monastic establishment still in activity. Formerly a Benedictine, since 2001 it has been affiliated with the order of the Monastic Fraternities of Jerusalem. It is located on the islet of Mont Saint-Michel, which itself is on the territory of the French commune named Le Mont-Saint-Michel in the Manche department in the Normandy region.

The Château de Rambouillet (pronounced ), also known in English as the Castle of Rambouillet, is a château in the town of Rambouillet, Yvelines department, in the Île-de-France region in northern France, 50 km (31 mi) southwest of Paris. It was the summer residence of the Presidents of France from 1896 until 2009, and it is now managed by the Centre des monuments nationaux.

The Château de Carrouges is a château, dating partly from the 14th century, located in the commune of Carrouges, in the Orne department, Normandy, northern France. It is unusual in its combination of an austere fortress with a comfortable residence. The original fortifications at Carrouges were besieged and destroyed by English forces during the Hundred Years War. After the war, the château was rebuilt by Jean Blosset, grand seneschal of Normandy, in the 15th century.
The Château d'Aulteribe is a castle located in Sermentizon, in the Puy-de-Dôme département, Auvergne, central France.

The Trophy of Augustus or Trophy of the Alps is a Roman commemorative monument in a ruined state, dating from 7-6 BC. AD, located in the commune of La Turbie in the Alpes-Maritimes, in France. It overlooks the principality of Monaco. Its Latin name is Tropæum Alpium.

The ancient site of Sanxay is a site which brings together several constructions dating from the 1st and 2nd centuries, located on the territory of the commune of Sanxay, in the department of Vienne, in France.

The Arc de Triomphe de l'Étoile, often simply called the Arc de Triomphe, is one of the most famous monuments in Paris, France. It is located at the western end of the Champs-Élysées, at the centre of Place Charles de Gaulle—formerly known as Place de l'Étoile—named for the star-shaped configuration formed by the convergence of twelve radiating avenues. Paving stones of different colors trace a stellar pattern on the plaza's surface, with its points reaching toward the centre of each avenue. The monument is situated at the intersection of three arrondissements: the 16th (to the south and west), the 17th (to the north), and the 8th (to the east). Commissioned to honor those who fought and died for France during the French Revolutionary and Napoleonic Wars, the Arc bears the names of French victories and generals engraved on its inner and outer surfaces. Beneath its vault lies the Tomb of the Unknown Soldier from World War I, marked by an eternal flame commemorating unidentified fallen soldiers.
The Palais-Royal, a monumental ensemble (palace, garden, galleries, theater) north of the Louvre Palace in the 1st arrondissement of Paris, is a key place in the history of France and Parisian life.
La Maison des Jardies, labeled Maisons des Illustres, is a residence located in Sèvres, in Hauts-de-Seine. It contains various objects and documents linked to Léon Gambetta, one of its famous owners.

The Château de Voltaire is located in Ferney-Voltaire (Ain) in France, close to the border with Switzerland and the city of Geneva. It was Voltaire's home between 1761 and 1778. It was listed as a historical monument in 1958 and acquired by the French State in 1999.

The Church of Saint Mary Magdalene (French: église Sainte-Marie-Madeleine ), less formally called La Madeleine (), is a Catholic parish church on Place de la Madeleine in the eighth arrondissement of Paris. It was planned by Louis XV as the focal point of the new Rue Royal, leading to the new Place Louis XV, the present Place de la Concorde. It was dedicated in 1764 by Louis XV, but work was halted due to the French Revolution. Napoleon Bonaparte had it redesigned in the Neoclassical style to become a monument to the glory of his armies. After his downfall in 1814, construction as a church resumed, but it was not completed until 1842. The building is surrounded on all four sides by Corinthian columns. The interior is noted for its frescoes on the domed ceiling, and monumental sculptures by François Rude, Carlo Marochetti and other prominent 19th-century French artists.

The Cemetery of Montmartre (French: Cimetière de Montmartre) is a cemetery in the 18th arrondissement of Paris, France, that dates to the early 19th century. Officially known as the Cimetière du Nord, it is the third largest necropolis in Paris, after the Père Lachaise Cemetery and the Montparnasse Cemetery.

The Place Vendôme (French: ; lit. 'Vendôme Square'), originally the Place Louis-le-Grand ('Louis the Great Square'), and later the Place Internationale ('International Square'), is a public square in the 1st arrondissement of Paris, located to the north of the Tuileries Gardens and east of the Église de la Madeleine. It is the starting point of the Rue de la Paix. Its regular architecture by Jules Hardouin-Mansart and pedimented screens canted across the corners give the rectangular Place Vendôme the aspect of an octagon. The original Vendôme Column at the centre of the square was erected by Napoleon I to commemorate the Battle of Austerlitz; it was torn down on 16 May 1871, by decree of the Paris Commune, but subsequently re-erected and remains a prominent feature on the square today.
The Bois de Vincennes (French pronunciation: ), located on the eastern edge of Paris, France, is the largest public park in the city. It was created between 1855 and 1866 by Emperor Napoleon III.

The Church of Saint-Germain l'Auxerrois (French pronunciation: ) is a medieval Catholic church in the 1st arrondissement of Paris, directly across from the Louvre Palace. It was named for Saint Germanus of Auxerre, a medieval bishop of Auxerre, who became a papal envoy and met Saint Genevieve, the patron saint of Paris, on his journeys. Genevieve is reputed to have converted Queen Clotilde and her husband, French king Clovis I to Christianity at the tomb of Saint Germain in Auxerre.

The American Church in Paris (formerly the American Chapel in Paris) was the first American church established outside the United States. It traces its roots back to 1814, and the present church building - located at 65 Quai d'Orsay in the 7th arrondissement of Paris, France - dates to 1931.

The Church of the Val-de-Grâce (French pronunciation: ) is a Roman Catholic church in the 5th arrondissement of Paris. The church was built as part of a royal abbey by Anne of Austria, the Queen of France, to celebrate the birth of her son, Louis XIV in 1638. Construction began in 1645 under the direction of architect François Mansart and was completed in 1665 by Gabriel Le Duc. The abbey and church were turned into a hospital during the French Revolution and then became part of the Val-de-Grâce Hospital, which closed in 1979. The church is attached to the diocese of the French military and is open to visitors at specified hours. Its dome is a landmark in the skyline of Paris.

The Grand Mosque of Paris (French: Grande Mosquée de Paris, pronounced ; Arabic: مسجد باريس الكبير), also known as the Great Mosque of Paris or simply the Paris Mosque, located in the 5th arrondissement of Paris, is one of the largest mosques in France. It comprises prayer rooms, an outdoor garden, a small library, a gift shop, along with a cafe and restaurant. In all, the mosque plays an important role in promoting the visibility of Islam and Muslims in France. Completed in 1926, is the oldest mosque in metropolitan France.

The Place de la Bastille (French pronunciation: ) is a square in Paris where the Bastille Prison once stood, until the storming of the Bastille and its subsequent physical destruction between 14 July 1789 and 14 July 1790 during the French Revolution. No vestige of the prison remains.

Père Lachaise Cemetery (French: Cimetière du Père-Lachaise , formerly Cimetière de l'Est, lit. 'Cemetery of the East') is the largest cemetery in Paris, France, at 44 hectares (110 acres). With more than 3.5 million visitors annually, it is the most visited necropolis in the world.

The Place Dauphine (French pronunciation: ) is a public square located near the western end of the Île de la Cité in the 1st arrondissement of Paris. It was initiated by Henry IV in 1607, the second of his projects for public squares in Paris, the first being the Place Royale (now the Place des Vosges). He named it for his son, the Dauphin of France and future Louis XIII, who had been born in 1601. From the "square", actually triangular in shape, one can access the middle of the Pont Neuf, a bridge which connects the left and right banks of the Seine by passing over the Île de la Cité. A street called, since 1948, Rue Henri-Robert, forty metres long, connects the Place Dauphine and the bridge. Where they meet, there are two other named places, the Place du Pont-Neuf and the Square du Vert-Galant.

The Palais-Royal (French: ) is a former French royal palace located on Rue Saint-Honoré in the 1st arrondissement of Paris. The screened entrance court faces the Place du Palais-Royal, opposite the Louvre. Originally called the Palais-Cardinal, it was built for Cardinal Richelieu from about 1633 to 1639 by architect Jacques Lemercier. Richelieu bequeathed it to Louis XIII, before Louis XIV gave it to his younger brother, Philippe I, Duke of Orléans. As the succeeding Dukes of Orléans made such extensive alterations over the years, almost nothing remains of Lemercier's original design.

The Church of Saint-Roch (French: Église Saint-Roch, pronounced ) is a 17th–18th-century French Baroque and classical style church in Paris, dedicated to Saint Roch. It is located at 284 rue Saint-Honoré, in the 1st arrondissement. The current church was built between 1653 and 1740.

The Church of Saint-Sulpice (French pronunciation:  ⓘ) is a Catholic church in Paris, France, on the east side of Place Saint-Sulpice, in the 6th arrondissement. As tall as Notre-Dame, it is the largest church in the city. It is dedicated to Sulpitius the Pious. Construction of the present building, the second on the site, began in 1646. During the 18th century, an elaborate gnomon, the Gnomon of Saint-Sulpice, was constructed in the church. Saint-Sulpice is also known for its Great Organ, one of the most significant organs in the world, and its titular organists, including Charles-Marie Widor and Marcel Dupré.

The Jardins des Champs-Élysées is a public park located in the 8th arrondissement of Paris. It occupies 13.7 hectares, and is located on both sides of the Avenue des Champs-Élysées between the Place de la Concorde on the east and the Rond-point des Champs-Élysées on the west and between Avenue Gabriel to the north and the Seine to the south. It includes within its boundaries the Grand Palais and the Petit Palais, as well as a theater and other buildings. It was one of the first parks in the city, laid out by André Le Notre in 1667, and was the site of the Paris International Exposition of 1855 and an important part of the Paris Universal Exposition of 1900, for which the Grand Palais and Petit Palais were created.

The Pont des Arts (French pronunciation: ) or Passerelle des Arts () is a pedestrian bridge in Paris which crosses the River Seine. It links the Institut de France and the central square (cour carrée) of the Palais du Louvre, which had been termed the "Palais des Arts" under the First French Empire.

The Arènes de Lutèce (, "Arenas of Lutetia") are among the most important ancient Roman remains in Paris (known in antiquity as Lutetia), together with the Thermes de Cluny. Constructed in the 1st century AD, this theatre could once seat 15,000 people and was used also as an amphitheatre to show gladiatorial combats.
Several cities have a Place de Catalunya:

The Musée des Arts et Métiers (French pronunciation: ; English: Museum of Arts and Crafts) is an industrial design museum in Paris that houses the collection of the Conservatoire national des arts et métiers, which was founded in 1794 as a repository for the preservation of scientific instruments and inventions.

This list of mosques in France is not exhaustive. It is particularly difficult to count the precise number of Muslim places of worship, because many of them are in spaces not originally built for this purpose. A mosque is above all a building designed for prayer and related activities of the communities concerned, otherwise they are simple prayer rooms, but which are sometimes called mosques for the sake of simplification.

The Passerelle Simone-de-Beauvoir (French pronunciation: ; initially known by the provisional name of passerelle Bercy-Tolbiac) is a bridge solely for pedestrians and cyclists across the Seine River in Paris. It is the 37th bridge on the Seine in Paris. It is located between the bridges of Pont de Bercy and Pont de Tolbiac and links up the 12th and 13th arrondissements of Paris. Its nearest Paris Metro station is Quai de la Gare.

input_name: Centre Pompidou - Musée National d'Art Moderne
wiki_description: The National Museum of Modern Art (MNAM) is a French museum dedicated to modern and contemporary art of the 20th and 21st centuries. It is located in Paris in the Georges-Pompidou center, where it occupies two levels (“Contemporary Art” on level 4 and “Modern Art” on level 5), in addition to the Brancusi workshop, temporary exhibition galleries and various other spaces linked to the museum. The collection is the second largest in the world after that of the Museum of Modern Art in New York and brings together more than one hundred and ten thousand works, only a part of which is exhibited on a rotating basis. The hanging is in principle revised every two years. Temporary exhibitions are also presented.

The Sainte-Anne de la Butte-aux-Cailles church, or formerly Sainte-Anne de la Maison-Blanche, is a Catholic religious building located in the 13th arrondissement of Paris, in the Butte-aux-Cailles district, at the intersection of rue de Tolbiac and rue Bobillot.

The Saint-Christophe-de-Javel church is a church in Paris located rue Saint-Christophe in the 15th arrondissement near the intersection with rue de la Convention in the Javel district, it is listed as a historic monument.
There are several Saint-Léon churches, all dedicated to Leo I, a Christian saint:

Saint Albert the Great (born Albrecht von Bollstädt), also known under the names Albert of Cologne and Albertus Magnus, born around the year 1200 in Lauingen and died November 15, 1280 in Cologne, is a German Dominican friar, philosopher, theologian, naturalist and chemist. Bishop of Regensburg for three years (1260-1263), he preferred to return to teaching and was a renowned teacher in the 13th century. The most famous of his disciples is Saint Thomas Aquinas.
The Saint-François-de-Sales church can designate several churches named in honor of Saint François de Sales:
Several Roman Catholic churches bear the name Saint-Antoine-de-Padoue church.

The Church of Marie-Médiatrice-de-Alles-les-Grâces, or Church of Marie-Médiatrice or Notre-Dame-de-Fatima Church is a Catholic church in the 19th arrondissement of Paris. Located at the crossroads of Boulevard Sérurier and Avenue de la Porte-du-Pré-Saint-Gervais, it was built between 1950 and 1954 by the architect Henri Vidal.

The Église de la Sainte-Trinité (French pronunciation: ) is a Roman Catholic church located on the place d'Estienne d'Orves, at 3 rue de la Trinité, in the 9th arrondissement of Paris. It was built between 1861 and 1867 during the reign of Emperor Napoleon III, in the residential neighborhood of the Chaussée d'Antin. It is in the ornate Neo-Renaissance or Second Empire Style, with a highly visible 65-meter-tall belfry.

wiki_name: Église protestante unie de Paris Passy-Annonciation
wiki_description: The United Protestant Church of the Annonciation is a Protestant parish whose temple is located at 19, rue Cortambert, in the 16th arrondissement of Paris. The parish is a member of the United Protestant Church of France.
The Saint-Lambert church in Paris or Saint-Lambert de Vaugirard church is a church located on rue Gerbert in the 15th arrondissement of Paris.

The Église Saint-Philippe-du-Roule is a Roman Catholic church located at 154 Rue du Faubourg-Saint-Honoré in the 8th arrondissement of Paris. Resembling a Roman temple. it was built in the style of Neoclassicism between 1774 and 1784 by architect Jean-François Chalgrin, best known for his design of the Arc de Triomphe. It was enlarged in 1845 by the architects Étienne-Hippolyte Godde and Victor Baltard.

The Saint-Pierre-de-Montrouge church is a parish church built in the second half of the 19th century to the plans of Émile Vaudremer at 82, avenue du Général-Leclerc in the 14th arrondissement of Paris (Petit-Montrouge district).
The Saint-Pierre-du-Gros-Caillou Catholic church is located at 92, rue Saint-Dominique in the 7th arrondissement of Paris (France).

The Saint-Serge Institute of Orthodox Theology (ITO), or simply Institut Saint-Serge, is a private higher education establishment outside of a contract, located in Paris, in the Combat district of the 19th arrondissement.
Saint Odile of Hohenburg gave her name to several places or religious buildings:
The Saint-Honoré d'Eylau parish is a Catholic parish in the 16th arrondissement of Paris.

The Saint-Pierre de Montmartre church is a Roman Catholic parish church located in the 18th arrondissement of Paris, at the top of the Montmartre hill, at no. 2 rue du Mont-Cenis, west of the Sacré-Cœur basilica.
The Saint-Denys-du-Saint-Sacrement church is located at 68 ter, rue de Turenne, in the 3rd arrondissement of Paris. The neoclassical architecture and decoration are typical of the early 19th century.

The Saint-Jean-Baptiste church in Belleville is one of the first churches of neo-Gothic architecture built in Paris. Located at 139 rue de Belleville, in the 19th arrondissement of Paris, it was built between 1854 and 1859.

The Saint-Jean-Baptiste de Grenelle church is a church in the 15th arrondissement of Paris. The bell tower surmounting the church, of medieval neo-Gothic spirit, contrasts with the antique inspiration of the rest of the building and gives it its unique appearance.
The Sainte-Marie des Batignolles church is a religious building located 77 place du Docteur-Félix-Lexigeois, in the current 17th arrondissement of Paris, in the Batignolles district.

Sven Lagerbring (originally Sven Bring; after being knighted, he wrote his name Sven Lager Bring), born February 24, 1707 in Klinta (Bosjökloster) and died December 5, 1787 in Lund, was a Swedish professor and historian.

The Jardin Catherine-Labouré is a park of about 7,000 square metres in Paris's Seventh Arrondissement, on Rue Babylone. This garden with grapevines and ornamental berries was the potager of the convent of the Daughters of Charity since 1633 and has been open to the public since 1977. There is a community garden along with an arbor-covered pathway.

Parc de la Villette is a public park located in the 19th arrondissement of Paris in France. It is located on the site of the former slaughterhouses of La Villette, built in 1867 by decision of Napoleon III and the prefect Haussmann and destroyed in 1974. It extends over 55 hectares including 33 of green spaces, making it the largest green space in the capital, in front of the Tuileries garden (25.5 ha), the Buttes-Chaumont park (25 ha) and the Luxembourg garden (23 ha).
Place de Rungis is a street located in the 13th arrondissement of Paris in France.
The square d'Anvers - Jean-Claude-Carrière is a square in the 9th arrondissement of Paris.

The Picasso Museum is the French national museum dedicated to the life and work of Pablo Picasso as well as the artists who were linked to him.

input_name: Musée Guimet (Musée National des Arts Asiatiques)
wiki_name: Musée national des Arts asiatiques - Guimet
wiki_description: The National Museum of Asian Arts, commonly called the Guimet Museum, is an Asian arts museum located in Paris, 6, place d'Iéna, in the 16th arrondissement. It was inaugurated in 1889 under the initial name of Museum of Religions. It has been a public administrative establishment since December 26, 2003.
Artcurial is a French auction house which has its headquarters at the historic Hôtel Marcel Dassault in Paris.

The Henri Cartier-Bresson Foundation (French: Fondation Henri Cartier-Bresson), also known as Fondation HCB, is an art gallery and non-profit organisation in Paris that was established to preserve and show the work of Henri Cartier-Bresson and Martine Franck, and show the work of others. It was set up in 2003 by the photographer and painter Cartier-Bresson, his wife, also a photographer, Franck, and their daughter, Mélanie Cartier-Bresson.

The Musée de Cluny (French pronunciation: ), officially Musée de Cluny-Musée National du Moyen Âge (lit. 'Cluny Museum-National Museum of the Middle Ages'), is a museum of medieval art in Paris. It is located in the 5th arrondissement of Paris, bordered by square Samuel-Paty to the south, boulevard Saint-Michel to the west, boulevard Saint-Germain to the north, and rue Saint-Jacques to the east.

input_name: Cité de l'Architecture et du Patrimoine
wiki_name: Cité de l'Architecture et du Patrimoine
wiki_description: The Cité de l'architecture et du patrimoine (French pronunciation: , Architecture and Heritage City) is a museum of architecture and monumental sculpture located in the Palais de Chaillot (Trocadéro), in Paris, France. Its permanent collection is also known as Musée national des monuments français (National Museum of French Monuments). It was established in 1879 by Eugène Viollet-le-Duc. The museum was renovated in 2007 and covers 9,000 square meters of gallery space. As a whole, the Cité de l'architecture et du patrimoine spreads across 22,000 square meters, which makes it the largest museum devoted to architecture in the world, even surpassing the Design Museum of London.

The Reuilly lawn, also called Reuilly clearing, is an open space of approximately 25 hectares located at the western end of the Bois de Vincennes, in the 12th arrondissement of Paris. It is the property of the municipality of Paris.

The Viaduc des Arts is a converted train line located in the 12th arrondissement of Paris which is now both a series of workshops for highly skilled artisans and, on the top level, the Promenade Plantée, a linear park. It was formerly the "Viaduc de Bastille," for the trains of the Paris-Bastille-Vincennes line.
The Serbian Orthodox Church (Serbian: Српска православна црква / Srpska pravoslavna crkva) or Patriarchate of Serbia is a canonical autocephalous jurisdiction of the Orthodox Church.

Bruno de La Salle is a French storyteller, singer, author, collector, director, organizer of storytelling festivals, teacher and radio producer born October 11, 1943 in Toulon, founder and artistic director of the Contemporary Conservatory of Oral Literature (CLiO), in Chartres then Vendôme.

input_name: Chapelle Notre-Dame de la Médaille Miraculeuse
wiki_name: Chapel of Our Lady of the Miraculous Medal
wiki_description: The Chapel of Graces of the Miraculous Virgin (French: La Chapelle du Grâce de Sainte Vierge Miraculeuse) or informally the Chapel of Our Lady of the Miraculous Medal, is a Roman Catholic Marian shrine located in Paris, France. It is dedicated to the Blessed Virgin Mary under the Marian title the Virgin of Miracles.

wiki_name: Liste d'odonymes se référant à Léon Gambetta
wiki_description: Many cities have named a public road (avenue, esplanade, square, street, bridge, etc.) in homage to Léon Gambetta (1838-1882), French political figure of the Third Republic.
Place du Marché-Saint-Honoré is a street in the 1st arrondissement of Paris, France, known for hosting a contemporary work by Catalan architect Ricardo Bofill at its center.

The Palais-Royal (French: ) is a former French royal palace located on Rue Saint-Honoré in the 1st arrondissement of Paris. The screened entrance court faces the Place du Palais-Royal, opposite the Louvre. Originally called the Palais-Cardinal, it was built for Cardinal Richelieu from about 1633 to 1639 by architect Jacques Lemercier. Richelieu bequeathed it to Louis XIII, before Louis XIV gave it to his younger brother, Philippe I, Duke of Orléans. As the succeeding Dukes of Orléans made such extensive alterations over the years, almost nothing remains of Lemercier's original design.
Place des Abbesses is located on the Butte Montmartre, in the Clignancourt district of the 18th arrondissement of Paris.

The Place Charles de Gaulle (French: ), historically known as the Place de l'Étoile (French: ), is a large road junction in Paris, France, the meeting point of twelve straight avenues (hence its historic name, which translates as "Square of the Star") including the Champs-Élysées. It was renamed in 1970, following the death of former President Charles de Gaulle. It is still often referred to by its original name; the nearby Métro and RER station retains the designation Charles de Gaulle–Étoile. Paris's Axe historique ("historical axis") cuts through the Arc de Triomphe, which stands at the centre of the Place Charles de Gaulle.
Place de Breteuil is a square in the 7th and 15th arrondissements of Paris, France.

The Basilica of Saint Clotilde (Basilique Ste-Clotilde) is a basilica church located on the Rue Las Cases, in the 7th arrondissement of Paris. It was constructed between 1846 and 1856, and is the first example of a church in Paris in the neo-Gothic style.
Place Saint-Fargeau is a street located in the Saint-Fargeau district of the 20th arrondissement of Paris.
The Church of St. Eustache, Paris (French: église Saint-Eustache, pronounced ), is a church in the 1st arrondissement of Paris. The present building was built between 1532 and 1633.

The Place des Victoires (French pronunciation: ; English: Victory Square, lit. 'Square of Victories') is a circular square in central Paris, located a short distance northeast of the Palais-Royal and straddling the border between the 1st and the 2nd arrondissements. The Place des Victoires is at the confluence of six streets: the Rue de la Feuillade, Rue Vide-Gousset, Rue d'Aboukir, Rue Étienne-Marcel, Rue Croix-des-Petits-Champs and Rue Catinat.

The Place de Clichy (French pronunciation: ), also known as the Place Clichy, is a city square situated in the northwestern quadrant of Paris. It is formed by the intersection of the Boulevard de Clichy, the Avenue de Clichy, the Rue de Clichy, the Boulevard des Batignolles, and the Rue d'Amsterdam.
Rue de Rome, Place de Rome and Cour de Rome are the names carried by several roads in the following cities:

The Place de la République (French pronunciation: ; English: Republic Square; known until 1879 as the Place du Château d'Eau, ) is a square in Paris, located on the border between the 3rd, 10th and 11th arrondissements. The square has an area of 3.4 ha (8.4 acres). Named after the First, Second and Third Republics, it contains a monument, the Monument à la République, which includes a statue of the personification of France, Marianne.

Born in the United States, urban art or street art emerged in Paris from the end of the 1960s. First confined to urban wastelands, the metro and the abandoned spaces of working-class neighborhoods in the North-East and South-East of the capital, it gradually took over all the districts of Paris, before becoming institutionalized from the 2010s. Originally clandestine and masculine, it gradually gained visibility, became more feminine and internationalizes. Supported by the Paris City Hall, the gallery owner Mehdi Ben Cheikh and the collector Nicolas Laugero Lasserre or collectives such as the Urban Art Federation, Le M.U.R, Art Azoï, it is now exhibited in galleries (Itinerrance, Mathgoth), museums (Art42, the Banksy museum or Fluctuart) and brings together ephemeral works (Tour 13 or Street Art Avenue) or long-lasting (Boulevard 13).

LVMH Moët Hennessy Louis Vuitton SE is a French group of companies, founded in 1987 by Alain Chevalier and Henry Racamier, which is today the world number one in the luxury industry in terms of turnover.

The Saint-Nicolas-du-Chardonnet church, located in Paris at 23 rue des Bernardins, at the corner of rue Saint-Victor in the 5th arrondissement of Paris, in the Saint-Victor district, next to the Maison de la Mutualité, was rebuilt in the second half of the 17th century on the site of a 13th century building, and completed in 1937.

Cambronne (French pronunciation: ) is an elevated station on Line 6 of the Paris Métro. Located in the 15th arrondissement, it is named after the nearby Place Cambronne and Rue Cambronne, which were in turn named after Viscount Pierre Cambronne (1770–1842), a general at the Battle of Waterloo. The station is at the location of the former Barrière de l'École-Militaire, a gate built for the collection of taxes as part of the Wall of the Farmers-General; the gate was built between 1784 and 1788 before it was demolished prior to 1859 amid Haussmann's renovation of Paris.
The Saint-François de Molitor church is a building in the 16th arrondissement and the only Catholic place of worship in the Saint-François-de-Molitor parish.

The 17th arrondissement of Paris is one of the twenty arrondissements of Paris. It is located on the right bank of the Seine to the northwest of the city. It is bounded to the west by Neuilly-sur-Seine and Levallois-Perret, to the south by the 16th and 8th arrondissements, to the east by the 18th arrondissement and to the north by Clichy-la-Garenne and Saint-Ouen-sur-Seine.

input_name: Institut Suédois | Svenska Institutet i Paris
wiki_description: Lars Olof Lennart Nilsson (born August 24, 1922 in Strängnäs and died January 28, 2017 in Stockholm) is a Swedish photographer, pioneer of medical photography.
Square Boucicaut is a square in the 7th arrondissement of Paris.

The Church of Saint Mary Magdalene (French: église Sainte-Marie-Madeleine ), less formally called La Madeleine (), is a Catholic parish church on Place de la Madeleine in the eighth arrondissement of Paris. It was planned by Louis XV as the focal point of the new Rue Royal, leading to the new Place Louis XV, the present Place de la Concorde. It was dedicated in 1764 by Louis XV, but work was halted due to the French Revolution. Napoleon Bonaparte had it redesigned in the Neoclassical style to become a monument to the glory of his armies. After his downfall in 1814, construction as a church resumed, but it was not completed until 1842. The building is surrounded on all four sides by Corinthian columns. The interior is noted for its frescoes on the domed ceiling, and monumental sculptures by François Rude, Carlo Marochetti and other prominent 19th-century French artists.
The Porte d'Auteuil is a gateway to Paris located in the 16th arrondissement in the immediate vicinity of the Auteuil district.

While Paris is encircled by the Boulevard Périphérique (Paris ring road), the city gates of Paris (French: portes de Paris) are the access points to the city for pedestrians and other road users. As Paris has had successive ring roads through the centuries, city gates are found inside the modern-day Paris.
Porte de la Muette is a gate in Paris, France, located in the 16th arrondissement, on the edge of the Bois de Boulogne.

The Place du Châtelet (French pronunciation: ) is a public square in Paris, on the right bank of the river Seine, on the borderline between the 1st and 4th arrondissements. It lies at the north end of the Pont au Change, a bridge that connects the Île de la Cité, near the Palais de Justice and the Conciergerie, to the right bank. The closest métro station is Châtelet

The Pont de l'Alma (French pronunciation: ; English: Alma Bridge) is a road bridge in Paris, France, across the Seine. It was named to commemorate the Battle of Alma during the Crimean War, in which the Ottoman-Franco-British alliance achieved victory over the Russian army in 1854. The bridge is known for being the site of the car crash that caused the death of Diana, Princess of Wales, in 1997.
Place Victor-et-Hélène-Basch, formerly but still sometimes referred to in common usage as “place d’Alésia”, is a square in the 14th arrondissement of Paris.
Marché Saint-Pierre is the name of several places:
Place des Vins-de-France is a street located in the Bercy district of the 12th arrondissement of Paris.
Place de Mexico is a square in the 16th arrondissement of Paris.
Square Miss.Tic is a square in the 5th arrondissement of Paris in homage to the artist, poet and visual artist Miss.Tic (1956-2022).

The Pavillon de l'Arsenal (French pronunciation: ) is the Paris Center for architecture and urbanism, a center for urban planning and museum located in the 4th arrondissement at 21, boulevard Morland, Paris, France. It is open daily except Mondays; admission is free.
Place Édith-Piaf is a street located in the Saint-Fargeau district of the 20th arrondissement of Paris.
The Montreuil Gate is one of seventeen gates built within the walls of Thiers in the mid-19th century to protect Paris, France.
Commerce station (French pronunciation:  ⓘ) is a station on line 8 of the Paris Métro in the Rue du Commerce, at the intersection with the Place du Commerce in the 15th arrondissement.
Émile Zola's house is located in Médan (Yvelines), 26, rue Pasteur.
The Square des Saint-Simoniens is a green space in the 20th arrondissement of Paris in the Saint-Fargeau district.
Place Octave-Chanute is a street located in the Saint-Fargeau district of the 20th arrondissement of Paris.

Passerelle Léopold-Sédar-Senghor, formerly known as Passerelle Solférino (or Pont de Solférino), is a footbridge over the River Seine between the 1st and 7th arrondissements of Paris. Opened in 1999, it was renamed after Léopold Sédar Senghor in 2006. The bridge owed its architect, Marc Mimram, the Prix de l'Équerre d'Argent the year of its opening.
Place Vauban is a square in the 7th arrondissement of Paris.
Square Alboni (or Square de l'Alboni) is a partly private road in the 16th arrondissement of Paris, France.

Bhaktapur - from bhakta, devotee and pura, the city - or Bhadgaon - or Khwopa in Newari - is a city in Nepal located in the Bagmati zone, 13 kilometers east of Kathmandu and at 1,401 meters above sea level. In the 2011 census, the town had 81,748 inhabitants.
