wiki_name: Liste d'odonymes se référant à Victor Hugo
wiki_description: Many cities have named a public road (avenue, esplanade, square, street, bridge, etc.) Victor-Hugo in honor of the French writer.

James Morrison, known as Jim Morrison, born December 8, 1943 in Melbourne (Florida) and died July 3, 1971 in Paris (France), is an American singer and poet, co-founder of the American rock group The Doors, of which he was a member from 1965 until his death.
The Pré-Catelan garden is a botanical park in the Bois de Boulogne in Paris which is located in the Pré Catelan area.

Édith Piaf, stage name of Édith Gassion, born December 19, 1915 in Paris and died October 10, 1963 in Grasse (Alpes-Maritimes), is a French singer, songwriter, composer and actress. Nicknamed “La Môme Piaf” in her early days, she is at the origin of several hits that have become classics of the repertoire, such as La Vie en rose, Non, je ne regrette rien, Hymne à l'amour, Mon légionnaire, La Foule, Milord, Mon Dieu and L'Accordéoniste.

The tomb of Oscar Wilde, entitled Flying Demon Angel, is a funerary monument located in Paris at the Père-Lachaise cemetery (20th arrondissement). It was sculpted from a twenty-ton block, from 1911 to 1914, by Jacob Epstein, a sculptor of American origin. Financed by Helen Carew, an admirer of the Irish writer, this monument is inspired by an Assyrian winged bull, kept in the British Museum. The grave is in Hopton Wood Stone, from Hopton. Since 1950, it has also housed the ashes of Robert Ross, Wilde's lover and executor.
The Porte de Bagnolet is a gate in Paris, France.
Promenade Pereire, in the center of the boulevard of the same name, is a square in the 17th arrondissement of Paris.
The Place de la Contrescarpe (French pronunciation: ) is a square in the 5th arrondissement of Paris.
Square Saint-Éloi is a square in the 12th arrondissement of Paris.

The Kagyu-Dzong Center (Tibetan: བཀའ་བརྒྱུད་རྫོང་, Wylie: bka' brgyud rdzong; 噶举中心) is a center of the Karma-Kagyu school of Tibetan Buddhism founded in 1974 by Lama Gyourmé, related to the 17th Karmapa, Orgyen Trinley Dorje. It is housed in a Tibetan and Bhutanese style temple which was inaugurated on January 27, 1985, built near the Bois de Vincennes Pagoda in Paris, headquarters of the International Buddhist Institute founded by Jean Sainteny.
Église Saint-Charles is a Roman Catholic church in Marseille, France. It is served by the Société des missionnaires de la miséricorde divine.
Place Franz-Liszt is a public road located in the 10th arrondissement of Paris.
Place de l'Alma is a square in the 8th and 16th arrondissements of Paris.
Place Jacques-Froment is located in the 18th arrondissement of Paris, France.
The Place de l'Odéon (French pronunciation: ; English: Odeon Square) is a semicircular square in the Odéon quarter in the 6th arrondissement of Paris.

The Pont de Bir-Hakeim (French: ; English: Bridge of Bir Hakeim), named after the 1942 battle in Libya, until 1948 the Pont de Passy (; Bridge of Passy), is a steel open spandrel deck arch bridge on stone masonry starlings, which crosses the River Seine in Paris. It connects the 15th and 16th arrondissements, passing over the northeast end of the Île aux Cygnes (the Isle of the Swans). The bridge, made of steel, was constructed between 1903 and 1905, in replacement of a footbridge that had been erected in 1878. The bridge has two levels: one for motor vehicles and pedestrians, the other being a rail viaduct (the Viaduc de Passy) built above the first one, through which passes Line 6 of the Paris Métro. The bridge is 237 metres (778 ft) long and 24.7 metres (81 ft) wide. The part crossing the Grand Bras ('great anabranch') of the Seine (west from the island) is slightly longer than the one crossing the Petit Bras ('small anabranch').
Rue Sorbier is a street located in the Père-Lachaise district of the 20th arrondissement of Paris.

Porte de Gentilly is a gate in Paris, France, located on the boundary between the Maison-Blanche district in the 13th arrondissement and the Parc-de-Montsouris district in the 14th arrondissement. It overlooks the town of Gentilly.

The Place des Ternes (French pronunciation: ) is a square in the 8th and 17th arrondissements of Paris, at the junction of the Avenue de Wagram, the Boulevard de Courcelles, the Rue du Faubourg-Saint-Honoré and the Avenue des Ternes. It has borne its present name since the late 19th century. In the middle of the square is the Paris Métro Line 2 station Ternes. It is located in the centre of one of the most vibrant communities of the city. The Place des Ternes is surrounded by various markets, parks, landmarks and local shops such as the Marché du Poncelet and Parc Monceau.
Place Saint-Ferdinand is a square located in the Ternes district of the 17th arrondissement of Paris.

The Tuileries Garden (French: Jardin des Tuileries, IPA: ) is a public garden between the Louvre and the Place de la Concorde in the 1st arrondissement of Paris, France. Created by Catherine de' Medici as the garden of the Tuileries Palace in 1564, it was opened to the public in 1667 and became a public park after the French Revolution. Since the 19th century, it has been a place for Parisians to celebrate, meet, stroll and relax. During the 2024 Summer Olympics and Paralympics, it was the site of the Olympic and Paralympic cauldron.
The Saint-Joseph-des-Nations church is a Catholic religious building located at 161 rue Saint-Maur in the 11th arrondissement of Paris (France).
The Pont de la Tournelle (French pronunciation: , Tournelle Bridge), is an arch bridge spanning the river Seine in Paris.

The Church of Saint-Nicolas-des-Champs (French: Église Saint-Nicolas-des-Champs; literally, St Nicholas-in-the-Fields) is a Catholic church in Paris' Third arrondissement. Early parts of the church, including the west front, built 1420–1480, are in the Flamboyant Gothic style, while later portions, including the south portal, mostly built 1576–86, are examples of French Renaissance architecture. It is notable particularly for its Renaissance carved sculpture, decoration and large collection of French Renaissance paintings in the interior.

input_name: Jardin des Grands Explorateurs Marco Polo et Cavelier-de-la-Salle
wiki_name: Jardin des Grands-Explorateurs Marco-Polo et Cavelier-de-la-Salle
wiki_description: The Jardin des Grands-Explorateurs Marco-Polo et Cavelier-de-la-Salle is a green space in the 6th arrondissement of Paris, France.
The Carré-de-Baudouin garden is a green space in the 20th arrondissement of Paris.

The pont Saint-Louis (French pronunciation: ) is a pedestrian bridge across the River Seine in the 4th arrondissement of Paris. It links the Île de la Cité with the Île Saint-Louis. It is served by the Cité stop of the Paris Metro.
The term Blancs-Manteaux is, originally, the nickname given in Paris from 1258 to 1277, to the mendicant order of the servants of the Blessed Virgin because of the color of their white coat.

input_name: Place de la Bataille de Stalingrad
wiki_description: The Place de la Bataille-de-Stalingrad is a square in the 19th arrondissement of Paris. It was named after the Battle of Stalingrad (1942–43), one of the major battles of World War II. The square lies at the intersection of the Canal de l'Ourcq and the Canal Saint-Martin.
Several towns have a Saint-Georges square:

The La Poste Museum is the La Poste Group's corporate museum dedicated to postal history and French philately. Opened in 1946, it had two sites in Paris. The current museum has been located at 34, boulevard de Vaugirard since 1973. Its collections have the Musée de France label under the supervision of the Ministry of Culture. The museum closed its doors in 2015 for a complete architectural and museum restructuring. Its reopening took place on November 23, 2019.

input_name: Paroisse Notre Dame de Grace de Passy
wiki_description: The Notre-Dame-de-Grâce church in Passy is located at 10 rue de l'Annonciation in the 16th arrondissement of Paris. It is a Roman Catholic church. Its bell tower is mentioned in the Ballade à la lune by the poet Alfred de Musset.

input_name: Galerie de Paléontologie et d'Anatomie comparée
wiki_name: Gallery of Paleontology and Comparative Anatomy
wiki_description: The Gallery of Paleontology and Comparative Anatomy (in French, Galerie de Paléontologie et d'Anatomie comparée) is a part of the French National Museum of Natural History (Muséum national d'histoire naturelle, MNHN). It is situated in the Jardin des plantes in Paris near the Gare d'Austerlitz.
Passage d'Enfer is a road in the 14th arrondissement of Paris located between Boulevard Raspail and Rue Campagne-Première.
Place Henri-Malberg (formerly Place des Grandes-Rigoles) is a street located in the Belleville district of the 20th arrondissement of Paris.
Notre-Dame-du-Bon-Conseil (Bon-Conseil for short; French: Our Lady of Good Counsel) may refer to:
Maubert–Mutualité (French pronunciation: ) is a station on Line 10 of the Paris Métro. Located in the 5th arrondissement, it is situated at the heart of the Latin Quarter on the Rive Gauche.

Mana (Japanese: 魔名) is a Japanese musician, songwriter, record producer, and fashion designer, best known as guitarist of the visual kei rock band Malice Mizer from their formation in 1992 until their indefinite hiatus in 2001. A year later, Mana formed the gothic metal band Moi dix Mois as his solo project.
Notre-Dame d'Auteuil (French pronunciation: ) is a Roman Catholic parish church on the Auteuil hill in the 16th arrondissement of Paris.

The Porte d'Orléans is one of 17 portes (city gates of Paris) in the Thiers wall, a defensive wall constructed in the mid-nineteenth century to protect Paris. The wall was demolished after the First World War, creating an open space that was subsequently built up. The Porte d'Orléans is now one of the main gateways to the capital, and is located in the 14th arrondissement of Paris.

The Fontaine des Innocents is a monumental public fountain located on the place Joachim-du-Bellay in the Les Halles district in the 1st arrondissement of Paris, France. Originally called the Fountain of the Nymphs, it was constructed between 1547 and 1550 by architect Pierre Lescot and sculptor Jean Goujon in the new style of the French Renaissance. It is the oldest monumental fountain in Paris.
The Sainte-Thérèse chapel located in Montmagny, in Val-d'Oise, in the Île-de-France region, is a Catholic religious building dependent on the diocese of Pontoise.
The Porte de Vincennes (French pronunciation: ) is one of the city gates of Paris (France) situated in the Bel Air neighborhood of the 12th arrondissement.

Saint-Augustin (French pronunciation:  ⓘ) is a station on Line 9 of the Paris Métro. Named after Place Saint-Augustin (itself named after Saint-Augustin church), the station opened on 27 May 1923 with the line's extension from Trocadéro. It is located in the 8th arrondissement.
The Saint-Ferdinand-des-Ternes church is a church in the 17th arrondissement of Paris.

wiki_name: Cité des sciences et de l'industrie
wiki_description: The Cité des sciences et de l’industrie (CSI) is a French establishment specializing in the dissemination of scientific and technical culture. Created on the initiative of President Valéry Giscard d'Estaing, its mission is to disseminate scientific and technical knowledge to a wide audience, particularly children and adolescents, as well as to arouse citizens' interest in societal issues linked to science, research and industry. The complex is located at Porte de la Villette, close to the ring road, on a site previously occupied by the Villette slaughterhouses, in the 19th arrondissement of Paris. It is at the heart of a system aimed at promoting scientific and technical culture: the Centers for Scientific, Technical and Industrial Culture (CCSTI). Along with the Philharmonie de Paris and the National Superior Conservatory of Music and Dance of Paris, it is part of the Parc de la Villette.

wiki_name: Cour d'honneur de l'hôtel des Invalides
wiki_description: The main courtyard of the Hôtel des Invalides, located in the northern part of the Hôtel des Invalides, in the 7th arrondissement of Paris, is a symbolic courtyard of this monument.

The Carrefour de l'Odéon is a square located in the Odéon district in the 6th arrondissement of Paris. It is frequently confused with Place Henri-Mondor, adjoining and delimited by Boulevard Saint-Germain, which is distinct from the latter in the land register.
The Pont de Sully (or Pont Sully; French pronunciation: ) is a bridge across the Seine in Paris, France.

input_name: Place de l'Hôtel de Ville — Esplanade de la Libération
wiki_name: Place de l'Hôtel-de-Ville – Esplanade de la Libération
wiki_description: The Place de l'Hôtel-de-Ville – Esplanade de la Libération is a public square in the 4th arrondissement of Paris, located in front of the Hôtel de Ville. Before 1802, it was called the Place de Grève. The French word grève refers to a flat area covered with gravel or sand situated on the shores or banks of a body of water.

The Notre-Dame-des-Victoires (French pronunciation: ) is a minor basilica located on rue Notre-Dame-des-Victoires in the 2nd arrondissement of Paris. It was begun as an Abbey church, and constructed between 1629 and 1740 in the French classical style. Its name was given by King Louis XIII, who dedicated it to his victory over the Protestants at La Rochelle in 1628 during the French Wars of Religion. Notre-Dame-des-Victoires is famous for the ex voto offerings left there by the faithful. Over 37,000 devotional plaques, silver and gold hearts, as well as military decorations, have been left at the basilica. The closest Métro station is 'Bourse'.

René Lefebvre de la Faluère, lord of la Faluère, is a French magistrate, born in Tours on August 6, 1632, died in Paris on March 21, 1708, first president of the Parliament of Brittany from May 5, 1687 until March 2, 1703 when he was replaced by Pierre de Brilhac. He was advisor to the king in his councils, president of the fourth chamber of inquiries of the Parliament of Paris, 1678, then first president of the Parliament of Brittany.

The Pont Charles-de-Gaulle (French pronunciation: , Charles-de-Gaulle Bridge) is a steel-reinforced concrete girder bridge straddling the river Seine in the eastern part of Paris. It is a one-way bridge carrying road traffic from the 13th arrondissement to the 12th arrondissement. Another one-way bridge further downstream, Pont d'Austerlitz, carries traffic in the opposite direction.
The Pereire brothers — Émile (1800-1875) and Isaac (1806-1880) — were French entrepreneurs and businessmen of the 19th century.
Place Sainte-Marthe is a street located in the Hôpital-Saint-Louis district of the 10th arrondissement of Paris.
Square Carpeaux is a square located in the 18th arrondissement of Paris, in the Grandes-Carrières area.
Place Sainte-Opportune is a street in the 1st arrondissement of Paris, France.
The Notre-Dame square - Place Jean-Paul-II is a square in Paris located opposite Notre-Dame Cathedral, on its square, which took the name of the Pope and Saint John Paul II in 2006.
Place du Maréchal-Juin is a square in the 17th arrondissement of Paris.
The Saint-Ouen gate is one of the seventeen gates opened in the walls of Thiers in the middle of the 19th century to protect Paris. It was built around 1840 in the former commune of Montmartre.
Place Martin-Nadaud is a square located in the 20th arrondissement of Paris.

The Roland-Garros stadium is a tennis stadium built in 1927 and located in the west of Paris at Porte d'Auteuil, on the edge of the Bois de Boulogne. Every year it hosts the French Open tennis tournament (created in 1891), as well as the Paris Major Premier Padel (since 2022).

The Louis-Vuitton corporate foundation, formerly the Louis-Vuitton corporate foundation for creation launched in October 2005, is a corporate foundation created by the LVMH group and its houses. Its objective is to perpetuate the sponsorship actions undertaken since 1990 by the group.

The Wall for Peace is a monument erected in March 2000 in front of the Military School, on the Champ-de-Mars, in the 7th arrondissement of Paris, and dismantled in June 2020 after years of protest from local residents. Since then, the new location of this monument on Avenue de Breteuil has been the subject of controversy.
The Notre-Dame-des-Champs church is located at 91, boulevard du Montparnasse, in the 6th arrondissement of Paris.
Porte de Vanves is a gate in Paris, France, located in the 14th arrondissement.
The Boulevard du Montparnasse (French pronunciation: ) is a two-way boulevard in Montparnasse, in the 6th, 14th and 15th arrondissements of Paris.

input_name: Temple protestant de l'Oratoire du Louvre
wiki_description: The Église réformée de l'Oratoire du Louvre is a historic Protestant church located at 145 rue Saint-Honoré – 160 rue de Rivoli in the 1st arrondissement of Paris, across the street from the Louvre. It was founded as a Catholic church in 1611, became the royal chapel of France under Louis XIII, and then became a Protestant Church under Napoleon I in 1811. It is now a member of the United Protestant Church of France.

Marguerite Lotti (in Italian: Margherita Lotti), called Sister Rita of Cascia (in Italian: sorella Rita da Cascia) commonly simplified to Rita, born in May 1381 in Roccaporena (Papal States) and died on May 22, 1457 in Cascia (Papal States), is an Italian widow who was admitted to the Augustinian order. She is known as the advocate of “desperate causes.” Canonized in 1900, her incorrupt body remains in the Basilica of Saint Rita in Cascia.
Place de la Chapelle is a square in the 18th arrondissement of Paris, France.
Square de Clignancourt is a street in the 18th arrondissement of Paris, France.
Porte Chaumont is a gate in Paris, France, located in the America district in the 19th arrondissement of the capital.
The Lycée Rodin is a French secondary and higher education establishment, located at 19 rue Corvisart, in the 13th arrondissement of Paris, not far from the Gobelins factory.
Rue du Pot-de-Fer is a street in the 5th arrondissement of Paris.
Place Léon-Blum, formerly but still sometimes called Place Voltaire, is a street located in the Roquette and Saint-Ambroise districts of the 11th arrondissement of Paris, in France.

wiki_name: Cathédrale Sainte-Croix de Paris des Arméniens
wiki_description: The Sainte-Croix de Paris Cathedral of the Armenians, former Saint-Jean-Saint-François church, is a cathedral of Armenian Catholic worship located 13-15 rue du Perche, in the 3rd arrondissement of Paris in the Marais district.
Place Jules-Joffrin is a square located in the 18th arrondissement of Paris, France.

The Saint-Jacques-Saint-Christophe de la Villette church, located 6, place de Bitche, between square Serge-Reggiani and place de Joinville, in the 19th arrondissement of Paris, is a Catholic parish church built between 1841 and 1844.
Place Rhin-et-Danube is a street located in the America district of the 19th arrondissement of Paris.
Place Flora-Tristan is a street located in the Plaisance district of the 14th arrondissement of Paris.

input_name: Place de la Porte de Saint-Cloud
wiki_description: The Place de la Porte-de-Saint-Cloud is a thoroughfare in the Auteuil district of Paris's 16th arrondissement.
Place de Wagram is a square in the 17th arrondissement of Paris.

Animation Digital Network, abbreviated ADN, formerly Anime Digital Network, is a VoD and simulcast platform born from the merger between KZPlay, belonging to Kazé, and Genzai, belonging to Kana Home Video, with the theme of broadcasting Japanese and Franco-Belgian animated series and feature films.
Place d'Iéna is located in the 16th arrondissement of Paris.

The Place Dalida (French pronunciation: ) is a square in Montmartre, in the 18th arrondissement of Paris, named after the Italian-French singer Dalida. Many fans and tourists visit the place to pay tribute to the artist.

Porte de la Villette is a gateway to Paris located in the Villette district in the 19th arrondissement of the capital. It separates Paris from Aubervilliers and Pantin (Seine-Saint-Denis). Historically, it is one of the seventeen gates opened in the walls of Thiers in the middle of the 19th century to protect Paris.
Lamarck - Caulaincourt is a station on line 12 of the Paris metro, located in the 18th arrondissement of Paris.
The Serge-Gainsbourg Garden is a public garden in the 19th arrondissement of Paris, France.
Place du Docteur-Félix-Lexigeois is a square in the 17th arrondissement of Paris.

The Église Saint-Paul-Saint-Louis (French pronunciation: ) is a church on rue Saint-Antoine in the Marais quarter of Paris. The present building was constructed from 1627 to 1641 by the Jesuit architects Étienne and François Derand, on the orders of Louis XIII. It was the first church in Paris to break away entirely from the Gothic style and to use the new Baroque style of the Jesuits, and it had an important influence on Parisian religious architecture. It gives its name to Place Saint-Paul and its nearest Metro station, Saint-Paul. Next door to the church is the Lycée Charlemagne, also founded by the Jesuits.
Pont d'Iéna (French: ; French for 'Jena Bridge') is a bridge spanning the River Seine in Paris. It links the Eiffel Tower on the Left Bank to the district of Trocadéro on the Right Bank.
Place Félix-Éboué, previously called Place Daumesnil, is a street located in the Picpus district of the 12th arrondissement of Paris.
Place Jacques-Bonsergent is a street in the 10th arrondissement of Paris, France.

Tizi Ouzou (in Kabyle: ⵝⵉⵣⵉ ⵡⴻⵣⵣⵓ, Ṯizi Wezzu; in Arabic: تيزي وزو; nicknamed “the capital of Djurdjura” and “col des Genêts”) is an Algerian commune located 30 km south of the Mediterranean coast and 100 km east of the capital Algiers. It is the capital of the Wilaya of Tizi Ouzou and the Daïra of Tizi Ouzou, in Kabylia.
Église Saint-Gervais-Saint-Protais, or Église Saint-Gervais-et-Saint-Protais, may refer to many churches around the world dedicated to the twins Saint Gervais and Saint Protais.
Square Henri-Collet is a square in the 16th arrondissement of Paris, in the Auteuil district.
Rue Mallet-Stevens is a public road in Paris inaugurated in July 1927 and located in the 16th arrondissement of Paris.
A public bench is a bench installed in a public place. It is part of urban furniture.
The Notre-Dame-de-Bonne-Nouvelle church, located at 25, rue de la Lune, in the 2nd arrondissement of Paris, is a Catholic parish church built from 1823 to 1830.

The Île-de-France regional council is the deliberative assembly of the French region of Île-de-France. The regional council is made up of 209 regional councilors elected for 6 years and has been chaired since December 18, 2015 by Valérie Pécresse (LR).

Porte de Champerret is a Paris gate in the 17th arrondissement of Paris.

The Notre-Dame-de-Consolation chapel is a chapel located at 23 rue Jean-Goujon in the Champs-Élysées district (8th arrondissement) in Paris. It is today entrusted to the Priestly Fraternity of Saint-Pie-X, by its owner, the Memorial du Bazar de la Charité association.
Several cathedrals are named Saint-Alexander-Nevsky Cathedral or Saint-Alexander-Nevsky Cathedral in honor of Alexander Nevsky:

The Cameroon football team is the national team that represents Cameroon in international men's football competitions, under the aegis of the Cameroon Football Federation (FECAFOOT). Also nicknamed the “Indomitable Lions” team.
Place des Antilles is a street located in the Sainte-Marguerite district of the 11th arrondissement of Paris, France.
Place de Varsovie is a street located in the Muette district and the Chaillot district of the 16th arrondissement of Paris.
Square de la Madone is a square in the 18th arrondissement of Paris, in the Chapelle district.

The Citizens' Convention for the Climate is an assembly of French citizens set up in October 2019 by the Economic, Social and Environmental Council, at the request of Prime Minister Édouard Philippe. This initiative brings together 150 volunteers selected at random from the French population, with the aim of designing a set of structuring measures “to achieve, in a spirit of social justice, reducing France's greenhouse gas emissions by at least 40% by 2030 compared to 1990”.

The Porte de Pantin is, today, a very important gate in Paris, France, located in the Villette district in the 19th arrondissement of the capital. It constitutes the main access to the town of Pantin from Paris.

The American Cathedral in Paris (French: Cathédrale Américaine de Paris), formally known as the Cathedral Church of the Holy Trinity, is one of the oldest English-speaking churches in Paris. It is the gathering church for the Convocation of Episcopal Churches in Europe, and is part of the worldwide Anglican Communion. The church is located in central Paris between the Champs-Elysées and the River Seine at 23 avenue George V in the 8th arrondissement. The closest métro stations are Alma – Marceau and George V .
The Musée national du Sport is a national sports museum located in the Grand Stadium of Nice, France.
The Porte d'Asnières is an important gate in Paris located in the 17th arrondissement. It owes its name to its proximity to the town of Asnières-sur-Seine.

The Hôtel des Invalides is a Parisian monument, located in the 7th arrondissement, whose construction was ordered by Louis XIV by the royal edict of February 24, 1670, to accommodate the invalids of his armies. Remaining faithful to this mission, in addition to the National Institution for Invalids, it houses the Saint-Louis des Invalides cathedral, several museums and a military necropolis including the tomb of Napoleon I. Seat of high military authorities such as the military governor of Paris, it also brings together a number of organizations dedicated to the memory of veterans and the support of wounded soldiers.
The Prost city is a former road in the 11th arrondissement of Paris, France, closed in 2006.
Place Raoul-Dautry is a square in the east of the 15th arrondissement of Paris.
Place Georges-Pompidou is a square located in the 4th arrondissement of Paris.
Square Van-Vollenhoven is a green space located in the Bel-Air district of the 12th arrondissement of Paris.

The Church of Saint-Séverin (French: Église Saint-Séverin, pronounced ) is a Catholic church in the 5th arrondissement, or Latin Quarter, of Paris, on the lively tourist street Rue Saint-Séverin. It was constructed beginning in 1230, then, after a fire, rebuilt and enlarged in the 15th to 17th centuries in the Flamboyant Gothic style. It was the parish church for students at the University of Paris, and is one of the oldest churches that remains standing on the Left Bank.

The Champs-Élysées-Marcel-Dassault roundabout, formerly but still sometimes referred to in common usage as the Champs-Élysées roundabout, is a square in the 8th arrondissement of Paris, capital of France.
The Alberto-Giacometti square is a square in the 14th arrondissement of Paris.
Passy Cemetery (French: Cimetière de Passy) is a small cemetery in Passy, in the 16th arrondissement of Paris, France.
Place Rodin is a street located in the Auteuil district of the 16th arrondissement of Paris.
The Place Pinel (English: Pinel Square) is a square and street in the 13th arrondissement of Paris.

The Porte Saint-Martin (French pronunciation: , St. Martin Gate) is a Parisian monument located at the site of one of the gates of the now-destroyed fortifications of Paris. It is located at the intersection of the Rue Saint-Martin from the south, the Rue du Faubourg Saint-Martin from the north and the grands boulevards Boulevard Saint-Martin from the east and Boulevard Saint-Denis from the west.

Porte d'Aubervilliers is an important gate in Paris, France, located at the junction of the Pont-de-Flandre district in the 19th arrondissement and the Chapelle district in the 18th arrondissement of Paris.

The Pont de Grenelle-Cadets de Saumur (French pronunciation: ), formerly known as Pont de Grenelle (English: Grenelle Bridge. "Cadets de Saumur" is the name of the students of the Saumur Cavalry School) is a bridge that crosses the Seine River in Paris, France. It connects the city's 15th and 16th arrondissements, and passes through the Île aux Cygnes. Constructed of steel, it is a girder bridge. The current bridge was constructed in 1966-68. It replaced an iron bridge that had stood since 1875. which had replaced the original wooden tollbridge built in 1827-29. The bridge passes behind a replica of the Statue of Liberty.
Passy Park is a public garden located in the 16th arrondissement of Paris.
Place Balard is a square in the 15th arrondissement of Paris which owes its name to the chemist Antoine-Jérôme Balard (1802-1876).
The Saint-Étienne-du-Mont church is a church located on the Sainte-Geneviève mountain, in the 5th arrondissement of Paris, near the Henri-IV high school and the Panthéon.

Charles de Batz de Castelmore, known as d'Artagnan, was a French musketeer born between 1611 and 1615 at Castelmore Castle, near Lupiac, in Gascony (in the current department of Gers) and died in Maastricht during the siege of this city on June 25, 1673, during the Dutch War.

The Notre-Dame-de-la-Croix church is a Catholic building located in the Ménilmontant district of the 20th arrondissement of Paris (France). This vast church (97 meters long, 38 meters wide, 20 meters high under the vault of the nave) combines neo-Romanesque and neo-Gothic elements. It has a bell tower 78 meters high as well as a monumental staircase which precedes its facade. It is one of the largest churches in Paris (the fourth by volume) and has been classified as a historic monument since 2017.

The Place Saint-Sulpice is a large public square, dominated on its eastern side by the Church of Saint-Sulpice. It was built in 1754 as a tranquil garden in the Latin Quarter of the 6th arrondissement of Paris.
The Esplanade du 9-Novembre-1989 is a square in the 15th arrondissement of Paris.
Arnold Daso Kisoka, born September 4, 2000, is a judoka from the Democratic Republic of Congo.

The Sainte-Élisabeth-de-Hungrie church is a Catholic religious building located in Paris (3rd arrondissement), dating from the 17th and 19th centuries. Firstly the chapel of the monastery of the nuns of the Third Order of Saint Francis (from 1646 to 1792) then the parish church (since 1802) in the Temple district, it usually hosts the religious celebrations of the sovereign order of Malta in Paris (since 1938).

wiki_description: The Hélène-Duc bridge, previously known as the Grange-aux-Belles bridge, named after the street that leads to it, is a swing-type road bridge, crossing the Saint-Martin canal, in the 10th arrondissement of Paris.
Saint-Jean de Montmartre (French pronunciation: ) is a Roman Catholic parish church located at 19 Rue des Abbesses in the 18th arrondissement of Paris.

Hillsong Church is an international evangelical Christian association of charismatic churches, based in Sydney, Australia. Its directors are Phil and Lucinda Dooley. The Church has faced various scandals, including sexual misconduct and abuse by pastors and misappropriation of donations.
Place Adolphe-Chérioux is a square in the 15th arrondissement of Paris.

The Porte d'Italie is one of the city gates of Paris, located in the 13th arrondissement, at the intersection of the Avenue d'Italie, the Boulevard Massena, the Avenue de la Porte d'Italie and the Rue Kellermann, facing Le Kremlin-Bicêtre.

Saint-Julien-le-Pauvre, in full Église Saint-Julien-le-Pauvre (French for Church of Saint Julian the Poor), is a Melkite Greek Catholic parish church in Paris, France, and one of the city's oldest religious buildings. Begun in Romanesque style during the 12th century, most of its architecture is Primary Gothic. It is situated in the 5th arrondissement, on the Left Bank of the Seine River, about 500 meters away from the Musée de Cluny and in the proximity of the Maubert-Mutualité Paris Métro station. It shares a city block with the Square René Viviani.

The Saint-Jean-Baptiste-de-La-Salle church is a Catholic church located in the Necker district of the 15th arrondissement of Paris, dedicated to Saint Jean-Baptiste de La Salle, founder in the 18th century of the Brothers of the Christian Schools and patron saint of educators.
Bagnolet is a French commune, located in the department of Seine-Saint-Denis in the Île-de-France region.

The Père-Lachaise crematorium-columbarium is an architectural ensemble made up of the first crematorium in France and a columbarium. The 19th century building built by architect Jean Camille Formigé is located inside the Père-Lachaise cemetery in Paris. It has been listed as a historic monument since 1995.
Square Jan-Doornik is a green space in the 16th arrondissement of Paris.

Place Henri-Frenay is a street located in the Quinze-Vingts district of the 12th arrondissement of Paris.

Saint-Bernard-de-La-Chapelle (French pronunciation: ), is a Neo-Gothic Roman Catholic parish church located at 11 rue Affre in the 18th arrondissement of Paris in the quarter known as he Goutte d'Or It takes its name from Bernard de Clairvaux, a monk from Burgundy in the 12th century who reformed the Cistercian Order. "La Chapelle" was the name of the neighbourhood, and came from a legendary chapel that was believed to have been built there by in 475 by Saint Genevieve over the burial place of Saint Denis, decapitated there in about 250 A.D.

Our Lady of Lebanon is the term by which the Virgin Mary, Mother of God, is invoked as patroness, protector and queen of Lebanon. This devotion has its origins at the beginning of the 20th century, when to celebrate the 50th anniversary of the proclamation (in 1854) of the dogma of the Immaculate Conception, the patriarch of the Maronite Church had the sanctuary of Our Lady of Lebanon built on the rock of Harissa (district of Kesrouan), north of Beirut, topped with a monumental statue of the Virgin Mary.
Rue Titon is a street in the 11th arrondissement of Paris, France.
Square Robert-Schuman is a square in the 16th arrondissement of Paris, running along the Bois de Boulogne and Boulevard Lannes.
The Pont d'Austerlitz is a bridge which crosses the Seine River in Paris, France. It owes its name to the battle of Austerlitz (1805).

The Pont de l'Archevêché (French pronunciation: , Archbishop's Bridge) is a bridge crossing the Seine river in Paris, France.

The Église Saint-Leu-Saint-Gilles de Paris is a Roman Catholic parish church in the 1st arrondissement of Paris. It has housed the relics of the Empress Saint Helena, mother of Constantine, since 1819, for which it remains a site of veneration in the Roman Catholic and Eastern Orthodox churches. In 1915 the French Ministry of Culture listed it as a monument of historical value.

The Notre-Dame-de-la-Nativité de Bercy church is a Catholic church located in the 12th arrondissement of Paris, in the Bercy district, on Place Lachambeaudie. It is also often called Notre-Dame de Bercy.
The Alleray garden is a green space in the 15th arrondissement of Paris, in the Saint-Lambert district.

The pont National (French pronunciation: ; named pont Napoléon-III from its construction until 1870) is a road and rail bridge across the Seine in Paris, to the east of the 12th and 13th arrondissements. With a total length of 188.5 metres (618 ft), it is made up of 5 masonry arches. Its rail part carries the Petite Ceinture, now disused, and its road part links boulevard Poniatowski to boulevard Masséna. Its nearest Paris Métro stations are Porte de Charenton and Cour Saint-Émilion.

The Place des Pyramides is a public square in the 1st arrondissement of Paris. It is located in the middle of the Rue de Rivoli, at its intersection with the Rue des Pyramides and the Avenue du General Lemonnier, at the eastern end of the Tuileries Garden.
Frank Shepard Fairey or Shepard Fairey, also known by the pseudonym Obey, is an American street artist, screenprinter, muralist and illustrator born February 15, 1970 in Charleston, South Carolina.
Place du Général-Catroux is a street in the 17th arrondissement of Paris.
A lift bridge generally refers to a bridge whose deck is movable and can be lifted horizontally.
The Rachmaninov garden is a green space in the 18th arrondissement of Paris.
Esplanade Saint-Louis is a street in the 12th arrondissement of Paris, France.

The Place du Palais-Bourbon is a historic square in the 7th arrondissement of Paris, France. It is named after the Palais Bourbon, the seat of the National Assembly of the French Parliament, located just north of the square.
The Jardins d’Éole are a park in the 18th arrondissement of Paris.

Notre-Dame-de-l-Arche-d'Alliance is a modern cube-shaped Catholic church located at 81 rue d'Alleray in the 15th arrondissement of Paris. It was designed by the firm Architecture-Studio and was built between 1996 and 1999

Place des Fêtes (French pronunciation: ) is a station of the Paris Métro, serving lines 7bis (towards Pré Saint-Gervais only) and 11 in the 19th arrondissement and the Belleville district. It is one of the deepest stations in the metro, at 22.45 m underground (Abbesses is the deepest at 36 m).

The pont de Tolbiac (French pronunciation: ) is a bridge across the Seine in Paris built between 1879 and 1882 by H.P. Bernard, and J.D.A. Pérouse. It crosses from the 12th to the 13th arrondissement, linking quai de Bercy to rue Neuve Tolbiac. Its nearest Paris Metro station is Cour Saint-Émilion.

The Pont de Bercy (French pronunciation: , Bridge of Bercy) is a bridge over the Seine in Paris. It links the 12th and 13th arrondissement of Paris by extending the Boulevard de Bercy and Boulevard Vincent-Auriol. In addition to the roadway, the bridge also carries Line 6 of the Paris Métro, between Quai de la Gare station and Bercy station.

The Caulaincourt Bridge is a road bridge in Paris. Almost unique in France, it allows you to cross the Montmartre cemetery via rue Caulaincourt. It is the first bridge in Paris built from riveted steel beams.
Square Carnot is a green space in the 12th arrondissement of Paris.
The Yitzhak-Rabin garden is a green space located in the Bercy park in the 12th arrondissement of Paris in France.

Protestantism is one of the three main denominations of Christianity, along with Catholicism and Orthodoxy. Widely understood, Protestantism is the set of Churches resulting from the Reformation, in other words, which do not recognize the authority of the Pope.
Place Édouard-Renard is a street located in the Bel-Air district of the 12th arrondissement of Paris.

The Place du Colonel Fabien (English: Colonel Fabien Square) is a square in Paris straddling the 10th and 19th arrondissements. Before the liberation of Paris, the square was called the Place du Combat ('Combat Square'), but it was renamed in honour of the French communist resistance hero Pierre Georges, whose nom de guerre was Colonel Fabien.

Saint-Dominique Church (French: Église Saint-Dominique) is a Roman Catholic church in Quebec City, Quebec, Canada. It was constructed between 1929 and 1930. In 2014, the church was added to the Répertoire du patrimoine culturel du Québec.

The term Black Church, or African American Churches, refers to predominantly Methodist Protestant churches that currently or historically serve predominantly African American congregations in the United States.

Jacques Fontaine born July 13, 1921 in Roubaix and died March 21, 2019 in Jerusalem, is a Dominican religious founder in 1960, with Bruno Hussar, of the Maison Saint-Isaïe (center of Jewish Studies of the preaching brothers in Jerusalem). In the summer, he developed a radically new mode of pilgrimage to the Holy Land: the Bible On the Ground and in the winter the study of the Bible in Hebrew associated with the liturgy of the day: the Bible Under the Earth. The 16th arrondissement of Paris constitutes one of the twenty arrondissements of Paris, located on the right bank of the Seine, to the west of the city. input_name: Cité-Refuge De L'Armée Du Salut Le Corbusier
wiki_description: Charles-Édouard Jeanneret-Gris, known as Le Corbusier, is a Swiss architect, town planner, designer, painter, sculptor, man of letters, poet and theorist naturalized French in 1930, born October 6, 1887 in La Chaux-de-Fonds in Switzerland and died August 27, 1965 in Roquebrune-Cap-Martin in France. He is one of the main representatives of the modern movement with, among others, Ludwig Mies van der Rohe, Walter Gropius, Alvar Aalto and Theo van Doesburg. He also rubbed shoulders with Robert Mallet-Stevens. Le Corbusier is known for being the inventor of the “housing unit”, a concept on which he began to work in the 1920s, an expression of theoretical reflection on collective housing. “The conforming size housing unit” (name given by Le Corbusier) will only be built during the reconstruction after the Second World War, in five examples, all different, in Marseille, Briey-en-Forêt, Rezé, Firminy and Berlin. It will become a solution to post-war housing problems. Its design envisages in the same building all the collective facilities necessary for life — daycare, laundry, swimming pool, school, shops, library, post office, meeting places. The architectural work of Le Corbusier bringing together seventeen sites (including ten in France, the others being spread over three continents) was classified as a UNESCO world heritage site on July 17, 2016. A European cultural itinerary entitled “Destinations Le Corbusier: architectural walks” was created at the beginning of May 2019. The work and thoughts of Le Corbusier were particularly influential on post-war generations of architects and widely disseminated, before entering, with the period of postmodernism, into a phase of significant and regular contestation,,,. It replaces the exterior load-bearing walls with reinforced concrete pillars placed inside the buildings. From then on, the facades no longer carry the upper floors, it is possible to clad them with light partitions and multiple, very large windows. He then plays with shapes and spaces, without having to take into account any alignment linked to the weights of the upper floors, this constraint having disappeared. Its main strength was to significantly reduce construction times. He was the first to use basic techniques and materials, making it possible to build an entire house, on several floors, in a few days, like his first complex, the Cité Frugès de Pessac, in the near suburbs of Bordeaux, a city made up of fifty small buildings and constructed at the rate of approximately one new building each week.

wiki_description: The Cité international universitaire de Paris (CiuP) is a foundation which, within its 40 Parisian houses, welcomes nearly 6,000 students, researchers, artists and high-level athletes from around the world.
The Saint-Georges de la Villette church is a Catholic church located at 112-114 avenue Simon-Bolivar in the 19th arrondissement of Paris.
The Saint-Germain de Charonne church, a Catholic religious building in the 20th arrondissement of Paris.

A meadow (/ˈmɛdoʊ/ MED-oh) is an open habitat or field, vegetated by grasses, herbs, and other non-woody plants. Trees or shrubs may sparsely populate meadows, as long as they maintain an open character. Meadows can occur naturally under favourable conditions but are often artificially created from cleared shrub or woodland for the production of hay, fodder or livestock. Meadow habitats as a group are characterized as semi-natural grasslands, meaning that they are largely composed of species native to the region, with only limited human intervention.

A Buddhist temple or Buddhist temple is a place of worship intended for practitioners of Buddhism. The stūpa, the chörten, the pagoda and the wat are examples of architectural structures typical of these temples.
Place Salvador-Allende (called Place de Santiago-du-Chili until September 11, 2003) is a square in the 7th arrondissement of Paris.

The Protestant Church in Germany (German: Evangelische Kirche in Deutschland, EKD) is the federal association of Lutheran, Reformed and United Protestant churches in Germany. It brings together a community of 20 autonomous and regional churches. The EKD, like its members, the regional churches, is recognized as a public establishment of worship. Its headquarters is in Hanover. All regional churches of the EKD are part of the Communion of Protestant Churches in Europe.
Place Roger-Madec is a street located in the Combat district of the 19th arrondissement of Paris.
The Porte de Vitry is a gate in Paris, France located in the Gare district south of the 13th arrondissement.

The Sacred Heart is a devotion to the heart of Jesus Christ, as a symbol of the divine love by which God took on human nature and gave his life for men. The theme of the Sacred Heart is particularly present in the Catholic Church as well as, on a lesser scale, in the Anglican Church and in certain Lutheran Churches.
Drakengard is a beat them all released on PlayStation 2 in 2003 (in Japan), published by Take-Two and by Square Enix, developed by Cavia.
Sainte-Rita (French pronunciation: ) is a municipality in Les Basques Regional County Municipality in Quebec, Canada.

A green theater is an artistically landscaped setting allowing you to attend live shows or cinema screenings in the open air. Often inspired by ancient amphitheaters in the semi-circular arrangement of stands or chairs oriented towards a stage space, it can be placed in a public garden surrounded by high hedges or fit more harmoniously into the natural environment. In the case of an aquatic environment, we speak of water theater.

Seraphim or Seraphim of Sarov (in Russian: Серафим Саровский), born Prokhore Isidorovitch Mochnin (in Russian: Про́хор Исидо́рович Мошни́н), born in Kursk on July 19, 1754 (or 1759) and died in the Sarov monastery on January 2, 1833, is an Orthodox saint.

The Pierre-et-Marie-Curie campus, named from its creation until 2019 Jussieu campus, located in the Saint-Victor district of the 5th arrondissement of Paris, is the main campus of the faculty of science and engineering of Sorbonne University.
Place de Torcy is a square in the 18th arrondissement of Paris, France.
Passage des Soupirs is a road in the 20th arrondissement of Paris, France.

L'Œuvre des Chantiers du Cardinal is an association created in 1931 by Cardinal Verdier to promote the construction and maintenance of Catholic churches in Paris and the Paris region. The financing provided by the Chantiers du Cardinal applies to buildings constructed after the law of separation of Churches and State of 1905, that is to say to buildings owned by the dioceses.
The Notre-Dame-des-Otages church is a Catholic parish church located at no. 81, rue Haxo in the 20th arrondissement of Paris.

The Notre-Dame-d'Espérance basilica of Charleville-Mézières is a minor basilica of the Catholic Church, this title given by Pius XII in 1946, located in Charleville-Mézières, in the Ardennes department. This Gothic style church, built from 1499, is lit by an astonishing array of modern stained glass windows made between 1954 and 1979 on the designs of the painter René Dürrbach.
Place Paul-Verlaine is a street located in the Maison-Blanche district of the 13th arrondissement of Paris.
The Solange-Faladé garden, formerly the Debergue - Rendez-Vous garden, is a green space in the 12th arrondissement of Paris, in the Bel-Air district.
Porte de Châtillon is a gate in Paris, France, located in the 14th arrondissement.
Place Bienvenüe is a street located in the Necker district in the 15th arrondissement of Paris.

The Notre-Dame-de-l'Assomption church in Passy is a church located on Place de l'Église-de-l'Assomption, accessible by 88 and 90, rue de l'Assomption in the 16th arrondissement of Paris.
Maison-Rouge is a French commune located in the department of Seine-et-Marne in the Île-de-France region.

The Notre-Dame de la Gare church is a parish church located on Place Jeanne-d'Arc in the 13th arrondissement of Paris, France. It takes its name from the district in which it is located, the Gare district. It was consecrated on November 11, 1859.
Nogent-sur-Marne (pronounced) is a French commune located in the Val-de-Marne department in the Île-de-France region.
The Saint-Gabriel church in Paris, of Catholic worship, is located rue des Pyrénées in the 20th arrondissement of Paris.

The Barrière du Trône (Trône Gate) was a toll barrier (barrière d’octroi) in the wall of the Fermiers généraux (the tax farmers’ enclosure) that was built around Paris in the 1780s. It was part of a wall that, just prior to the French Revolution, surrounded Paris. The purpose of the wall, which was designed by Claude Nicolas Ledoux, was to facilitate the collection of municipal duties on merchandise entering Paris by reducing smuggling and fraud. It is located in eastern Paris and straddles the 11th arrondissement and the 12th arrondissement. The barrier takes its name from its location on the former Place du Trône, now called place de la Nation.

Omar ibn al-Khattâb (Arabic: عُمَر إِبْن ٱلْخَطّاب‎), born in 584 in Mecca and murdered on November 7, 644 in Medina, is a companion of Muhammad, the prophet of Islam, and is part of the Banu Adi clan (in) of the tribe Quraysh.
Square Courteline is a small municipal green space in the 12th arrondissement of Paris.

input_name: Esplanade de la Bibliothèque Nationale de France
wiki_description: The National Library of France (BnF or BNF), so called since 1994, is the national library of the French Republic, inaugurated under this new name on March 30, 1995 by the President of the Republic, François Mitterrand. Heiress to the royal collections built up since the Middle Ages, it has one of the richest funds in the world.
The Pont des Invalides (French pronunciation: ) is the lowest bridge traversing the Seine in Paris.
The former Saint-Hippolyte church in Paris is a former Catholic place of worship in the Faubourg Saint-Marcel in the current Croulebarbe district of the 13th arrondissement of Paris.

The German Evangelical Church (German: Deutsche Evangelische Kirche) was a successor to the German Protestant Church Confederation from 1933 until 1945. It is also known in English as the Protestant Reich Church (German: Evangelische Reichskirche) and colloquially as the Reich Church (German: Reichskirche).

A bandstand is a construction for entertainment, typical of the 19th and early 20th century layout of towns and parks, very open, symmetrical in relation to the central axis (panoptic shape) and polygonal or, more rarely, circular in plan.
On the Black Paths is an autobiographical story by Sylvain Tesson published on October 13, 2016.
Rue Jean-Jaurès is a road in the French commune of Levallois-Perret.
Porte de Clignancourt (French pronunciation: ) is a station of the Paris Métro, the northern terminus of line 4, situated in the 18th Arrondissement.
Photoquai is a biennial exhibition created in 2007 by the Quai Branly museum and dedicated to non-Western photography. The last edition took place in 2015.

Saint-Laurent (French pronunciation:  ⓘ) is a Catholic church in the 10th arrondissement of Paris at 68 bis Boulevard de Magenta. A series of churches occupied the site since the 10th century. It is named for Saint Lawrence, an early Christian martyr who was executed in Rome by the Roman Emperor Valerian in 258 AD. It has been listed since 2016 as a monument historique by the French Ministry of Culture.

The Quartier asiatique (French pronunciation: , Asian Quarter), also called Triangle de Choisy () or Petite Asie (; Chinese: 巴黎唐人街, Vietnamese: Phố Tàu Paris) is the largest commercial and cultural center for the population of East Asian and Southeast Asian origin of Paris. It is located in the southeast of the 13th arrondissement in an area that contains many high-rise apartment buildings. Despite its status as a "Chinatown", the neighborhood also contains significant Vietnamese, Laotian and Cambodian populations.
Villa Flore is a lane in the 16th arrondissement of Paris, France.

The Place de la Bourse (French pronunciation: , "Stock Exchange Square") is a square in Bordeaux, France, and one of the city's most recognisable sights. Built from 1730 to 1775 along the river Garonne, it was a multi-building development designed by the architect Jacques Gabriel and his son Ange-Jacques Gabriel. It is within the historic part of the city that has been recognized on the UNESCO World Heritage List as "an outstanding urban and architectural ensemble" of the 18th century.
Rue du Château-des-Rentiers is a street located in the Gare district of the 13th arrondissement of Paris.

The original Tabernacle is the tent that housed the Ark of the Covenant in the time of Moses. Its chief architect, appointed directly by God to Moses, is Béséléel. In the Hebrew Bible and the Old Testament, the tabernacle was to be the temporary habitation of God, his residence and the rallying center of his people.

wiki_name: Tombeau de Napoléon Ier aux Invalides
wiki_description: The tomb of Napoleon I is located in the Hôtel des Invalides, a building designed in the 17th century by Libéral Bruand and Jules-Hardouin Mansart, then transformed into a pantheon of military glories by Napoleon when he transferred the tomb of Marshal de Turenne there. If Napoleon died on May 5, 1821 on the island of Saint Helena, the project for his tomb in Les Invalides only began after the announcement, in May 1840, of the return of the body (or “ashes”) of the Emperor. This announcement was followed, on June 10 of the same year, by the vote of a law fixing the place of burial. Submitted to the competition, the construction of the monument ultimately fell to Louis Visconti. Napoleon's body returned to his tomb on April 2, 1861, almost twenty years after the decision to bury him at Les Invalides.
Rue de Rennes is a street in the 6th arrondissement of Paris. It is a major shopping artery on the left bank of the capital.
Esplanade Saint-Louis is a street in the 12th arrondissement of Paris, France.
Place d'Alleray is a street located in the Saint-Lambert district in the 15th arrondissement of Paris.
Place Falguière is a street located in the Necker district and the Saint-Lambert district of the 15th arrondissement of Paris.

The wall of the Fermiers généraux (French: mur des Fermiers généraux, pronounced ) was one of the several city walls of Paris built between the early Middle Ages and the mid 19th century. The purpose of the wall of the Fermiers généraux was to facilitate collection of municipal taxes on merchandise entering Paris.

The Pavillon Carré de Baudouin is an 18th century building located rue de Ménilmontant in the 20th arrondissement of Paris, which was converted into a cultural space open to the public in June 2007. The place is managed by the city of Paris and the town hall of the 20th arrondissement of Paris and entry is free.

wiki_name: Statue Charles de Gaulle à Varsovie
wiki_description: The statue of Charles de Gaulle in Warsaw is located in front of the Banking and Financial Center (pl) building, at the Charles de Gaulle roundabout in the Śródmieście district of Warsaw. It was installed there on May 15, 2005. It is a copy of the monument erected in 2000 on the Avenue des Champs-Élysées in Paris.

Jean-Auguste-Dominique Ingres (/ʒɑ̃ ogyst dɔminik ɛ̃gʁ/), born August 29, 1780 in Montauban and died January 14, 1867 in Paris, is a French painter who was also an excellent musician - he was second violin with the Toulouse Orchestra - which led him to become friends with the greatest violinists of his time, Niccolo Paganini and Pierre Baillot.

Ferdinand Foch, born October 2, 1851 in Tarbes (Hautes-Pyrénées) and died March 20, 1929 in Paris (Seine), is a French soldier. Trained at the École Polytechnique then at the École de l'Artillery, he reached the rank of major general and distinguished himself as generalissimo of the Allied Forces on the Western Front during the First World War in 1918. He was elevated to the rank of Marshal of France the same year.
The Villa des Lilas is a lane in the 19th arrondissement of Paris, France.
Place d'Aligre is located in the middle of Rue d'Aligre, in the 12th arrondissement of Paris, France.
Paris has around twenty mosques, as well as numerous prayer rooms. Some districts have neither mosque nor prayer room. For mosques located outside Paris, see the List of mosques in France page.

The Boulevard Richard-Lenoir (French pronunciation: ), running from the Bastille to the Avenue de la République, is one of the wide tree-lined boulevards driven through Paris by Baron Haussmann during the Second French Empire of Napoleon III.

The Notre-Dame-du-Saint-Sacrement Catholic chapel is located at 20 rue Cortambert in the 16th arrondissement of Paris. This is the mother house of the Sisters Servants of the Most Holy Sacrament, a congregation founded by Pierre-Julien Eymard.
Jussieu (French pronunciation: ) is a station on lines 7 and 10 of the Paris Métro in the eastern part of the Latin Quarter in the 5th arrondissement.

The 17th arrondissement of Paris is one of the twenty arrondissements of Paris. It is located on the right bank of the Seine to the northwest of the city. It is bounded to the west by Neuilly-sur-Seine and Levallois-Perret, to the south by the 16th and 8th arrondissements, to the east by the 18th arrondissement and to the north by Clichy-la-Garenne and Saint-Ouen-sur-Seine.

wiki_name: Coupe arabe des nations de football 1998
wiki_description: The 1998 Arab Nations Cup is the 7th edition of the Arab Football Cup. The capital of Qatar, Doha, hosted the competition. Saudi Arabia won the tournament for the first time.
Place du Château-Rouge is a square in the 18th arrondissement of Paris.
A tropical garden is a garden made up of plants from the tropics.

The Place Beauvau (English: Beauvau Square) is a public square in the 8th arrondissement of Paris, at the intersection of the Rue du Faubourg-Saint-Honoré, the Avenue de Marigny, the Rue des Saussaies and the Rue de Miromesnil. It is located in the La Madeleine neighbourhood, next to the Élysée Palace.
Place Claude-Bourdet is a street located in the Croulebarbe district of the 13th arrondissement.

The Trevi Fountain (in Italian: fontana di Trevi) is the largest and one of the most famous fountains in Rome. Built between 1732 and 1762, it is located in the Rione of Trevi, on Piazza di Trevi, and backs onto the Palazzo Poli.

input_name: Jardin Botanique du Jardin des Plantes
wiki_description: The Paris Plant Garden, or Jardin des Plantes, located in the 5th arrondissement of Paris, is a botanical, ecological and zoological park, headquarters and main site of the National Museum of Natural History, which also has other sites in Paris and the provinces. As a space of the research institution that is the Museum, the Jardin des Plantes is, in this respect, a campus. In addition to the green spaces specific to a garden (beds, botanical spaces, trees, English garden, French perspective, etc.), the Jardin des Plantes also has a menagerie, greenhouses, and scientific exhibition buildings including a Mineralogy gallery and a Paleontology gallery. The garden itself is open free to the public during the day; There is a fee for the Museum galleries and the Menagerie. It has been listed as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in the Paris, banks of the Seine property since 2024.

Baptism or Baptist Christianity is an evangelical Christian movement, founded by the English John Smyth and Thomas Helwys in Holland in 1609. The movement professes the beliefs of the professing Church, including in particular the new birth and the baptism of the believer, stemming from Anabaptism. Churches belonging to the movement are called Baptist Churches.

The Sacré-Cœur church, located in Gentilly, avenue Paul-Vaillant-Couturier, is also that of the Cité international universitaire de Paris. Its high bell tower and its neo-Romanesque and neo-Byzantine style make it a well-known element of the Parisian landscape.

input_name: Temple bouddhiste de l’association des Teochew de France
wiki_description: The Asian districts of Paris are Parisian districts where a significant proportion of the population of Asian origin is represented with businesses and restaurants linked to their cultures of origin.

Disneyland Park (Disneyland Park in English) is a theme park of the Walt Disney Company located in France, in Marne-la-Vallée in Seine-et-Marne, and which opened its doors on April 12, 1992. It is part of the Disneyland Paris leisure complex, formerly called Euro Disney Resort then Disneyland Resort Paris. The resort is majority owned by the Walt Disney Company via Euro Disney SCA with 97.08% of the shares.

La Maison du canal is a detective novel by Georges Simenon published by Fayard, with the original edition having a cover designed by Bernard Bécan, in 1933. It is part of its author's series of “hard novels”.
A fitness trail—also called a sports trail or fitness trail—is a sports walk punctuated by a set of physical or meditative activities, generally in a natural setting or an urban park.
Place de l’École-Militaire is a square in the 7th arrondissement of Paris.
The Henri-Sauvage garden, formerly Square Amiraux - Boinod, is a green space in the 18th arrondissement of Paris.

The Place du Louvre (French pronunciation: ) is a square immediately to the east of the Palais du Louvre in Paris, France. To the south is the Quai du Louvre and beyond that is the River Seine. The Hôtel du Louvre is also located here, between the Louvre Palace and the Palais Royal.
The Biopark garden is a green space in the 13th arrondissement of Paris, in the Gare district.

Art Deco (abbreviation of “decorative art”) is an artistic movement of global scope born gradually in the 1910s and which came into full bloom during the 1920s, before slowly declining from the 1930s. It embraces all artistic activities and crafts. The “Art Deco style” takes its name from the International Exhibition of Modern Decorative and Industrial Arts which was held in Paris in 1925.

The Fontaine de l'Observatoire is a monumental fountain located in the Jardin Marco Polo, south of the Jardin du Luxembourg in the 6th arrondissement of Paris, with sculpture by Jean-Baptiste Carpeaux. It was dedicated in 1874. It is also known as the Fontaine des Quatre-Parties-du-Monde, for the four parts of the world embodied by its female figures, or simply the Fontaine Carpeaux.
Square de la Salamandre is a square in the 20th arrondissement of Paris.

The Revelation of the Pyramids is a pseudoscientific documentary, directed by Patrice Pouillard and released in 2010, then widely distributed on the internet from 2012. Written by Patrice Pouillard and Jacques Grimault, the film highlights pseudohistorical theories put forward by the latter.

The Marmottan Museum, which became the Marmottan Monet Museum in the 1990s, is a fine arts museum located in Paris. It notably presents a collection of art objects and paintings from the First Empire, as well as works by impressionist painters including the largest collection in the world of works by Claude Monet.

Philippe Leclerc de Hauteclocque, better known as General Leclerc or Marshal Leclerc, born Philippe de Hauteclocque on November 22, 1902 in Belloy-Saint-Léonard (Somme) and died in a plane crash on November 28, 1947 near Colomb-Béchar (French Algeria), is a French soldier, one of the main military leaders of Free France during the Second World War. A major figure of the Liberation, he is particularly known for having commanded the 2nd Armored Division.
Place de Passy is a street located in the Muette district of the 16th arrondissement of Paris.
The Botanical Garden of Brussels (in Dutch: Kruidtuin van Brussel), is a green space in Saint-Josse-ten-Noode in the Brussels-Capital region in Belgium.
The Church of the Eucharistic Heart of Jesus is a Catholic church located rue du Lieutenant-Chauré in the 20th arrondissement of Paris.

wiki_description: Square Serge-Reggiani, a green space in the 19th arrondissement of Paris.

The Museum of Fairground Arts (officially "Pavillons de Bercy · Musée des arts forains") is located in the Bercy district in the 12th arrondissement of Paris, at the southeastern end of Bercy Park. This museum presents a collection of show objects from the 19th and 20th centuries.

Édith Piaf, stage name of Édith Gassion, born December 19, 1915 in Paris and died October 10, 1963 in Grasse (Alpes-Maritimes), is a French singer, songwriter, composer and actress. Nicknamed “La Môme Piaf” in her early days, she is at the origin of several hits that have become classics of the repertoire, such as La Vie en rose, Non, je ne regrette rien, Hymne à l'amour, Mon légionnaire, La Foule, Milord, Mon Dieu and L'Accordéoniste.
The Lily-Laskine garden is a green space in the 17th arrondissement of Paris, France.
A Masonic lodge is a civil association - sometimes referred to as a civil brotherhood - formed by a small group of members of Freemasonry at the local level.

Place Napoléon-III is a street located in the Saint-Vincent-de-Paul district of the 10th arrondissement of Paris. It is located just in front of the Gare du Nord, of which it constitutes a large part of the square.
Porte de Montrouge is a gate in Paris, France, located in the 14th arrondissement.

The Rue Crémieux is a one-block pedestrian street in the 12th arrondissement of Paris, originally built as workers' housing. The street has been widely recommended to tourists for its quaint painted housefronts, and has become a popular destination for filming and for social media photos.

Space Invaders is a 1978 shoot 'em up video game developed and published by Taito for arcades. It was released in Japan in April 1978, and released overseas by Midway Manufacturing later that year. Space Invaders was the first video game with endless gameplay and the first fixed shooter, setting the template for the genre. The goal is to defeat waves of descending aliens with a horizontally moving laser cannon to earn as many points as possible.
Esplanade Henri-de-France is a square in the 15th arrondissement of Paris, France.

Porte de Clichy station (French pronunciation: ) is a station on Line 13 and Line 14 of the Paris Métro and RER C, as well as a stop on Île-de-France tramway Line 3b. Located in the 17th arrondissement, the Métro station is situated on the northwestern branch of Line 13, under the Avenue de Clichy. It serves the Tribunal de grande instance de Paris. The station is named after the Porte de Clichy, a gate in the nineteenth century Thiers wall of Paris, which led to Clichy.

The Godfather: Part II, or The Godfather II in Quebec, is an American film directed by Francis Ford Coppola, released in 1974. It follows the film The Godfather, released two years earlier, and precedes The Godfather, Part 3 (released in 1990).

Charlie Kirk (/ˈt͡ʃɑɹli ˈkɝk/), born October 14, 1993 in Arlington Heights (Illinois) and murdered on September 10, 2025 in Orem (Utah), is an American far-right political activist, conservative influencer and Christian nationalist.
Square Sainte-Hélène is a square in the 18th arrondissement of Paris.

input_name: Deuxième Eglise De La Science Chrétienne , Paris
wiki_description: Christian Science (or Christian Science in English) is a religious movement. It defines itself as the “Science of Christ”. Its founder, the American self-taught theologian Mary Baker Eddy, believes she rediscovered in 1866 the laws applied by Jesus in healing the sick and resolving the vagaries of life, laws supposedly demonstrable today. Her observation of the various healings and resolutions obtained on the basis of her theory proves, according to her, its validity. Thus, Christian Science is “Christian” in the sense that it is based on the teachings of Jesus of Nazareth as expounded in the New Testament. Christian Science aims to be a practical religion allowing the application of demonstrable divine laws.

House Targaryen is one of the main houses in the universe created by George R. R. Martin, appearing in the Game of Thrones book series and the novel Fire and Blood, as well as the television adaptations Game of Thrones and House of the Dragon. Coming from ancient Valyria, she survived the Scourge by taking refuge on the island of Dragonstone, then reigning for three hundred years over Westeros. Associated with dragons, the dynasty's coat of arms represents a three-headed red dragon on a black field. In classical heraldry, its blazon is: “Sable with a three-headed dragon gules.” »
The André Léo footbridge is a pedestrian footbridge spanning the Reuilly garden, in the 12th arrondissement of Paris, France.

Charles-Édouard Jeanneret-Gris, known as Le Corbusier, is a Swiss architect, town planner, designer, painter, sculptor, man of letters, poet and theorist naturalized French in 1930, born October 6, 1887 in La Chaux-de-Fonds in Switzerland and died August 27, 1965 in Roquebrune-Cap-Martin in France. He is one of the main representatives of the modern movement with, among others, Ludwig Mies van der Rohe, Walter Gropius, Alvar Aalto and Theo van Doesburg. He also rubbed shoulders with Robert Mallet-Stevens. Le Corbusier is known for being the inventor of the “housing unit”, a concept on which he began to work in the 1920s, an expression of theoretical reflection on collective housing. “The conforming size housing unit” (name given by Le Corbusier) will only be built during the reconstruction after the Second World War, in five examples, all different, in Marseille, Briey-en-Forêt, Rezé, Firminy and Berlin. It will become a solution to post-war housing problems. Its design envisages in the same building all the collective facilities necessary for life — daycare, laundry, swimming pool, school, shops, library, post office, meeting places. The architectural work of Le Corbusier bringing together seventeen sites (including ten in France, the others being spread over three continents) was classified as a UNESCO world heritage site on July 17, 2016. A European cultural itinerary entitled “Destinations Le Corbusier: architectural walks” was created at the beginning of May 2019. The work and thoughts of Le Corbusier were particularly influential on post-war generations of architects and widely disseminated, before entering, with the period of postmodernism, into a phase of significant and regular contestation,,,. It replaces the exterior load-bearing walls with reinforced concrete pillars placed inside the buildings. From then on, the facades no longer carry the upper floors, it is possible to clad them with light partitions and multiple, very large windows. He then plays with shapes and spaces, without having to take into account any alignment linked to the weights of the upper floors, this constraint having disappeared. Its main strength was to significantly reduce construction times. He was the first to use basic techniques and materials, making it possible to build an entire house, on several floors, in a few days, like his first complex, the Cité Frugès de Pessac, in the near suburbs of Bordeaux, a city made up of fifty small buildings and constructed at the rate of approximately one new building each week.

wiki_description: The CentQuatre is a Parisian public cultural cooperation establishment, open since October 11, 2008 on the site of the former Municipal Funeral Service, at 104 rue d'Aubervilliers, in the 19th arrondissement of Paris.

Notre Dame de Lourdes (or Notre-Dame-de-Lourdes) is French for "Our Lady of Lourdes", which refers to the Marian apparition that is reported to have appeared before various individuals in separate occasions around Lourdes, France.

Hillsong Church is an international evangelical Christian association of charismatic churches, based in Sydney, Australia. Its directors are Phil and Lucinda Dooley. The Church has faced various scandals, including sexual misconduct and abuse by pastors and misappropriation of donations.

Le Daron is a Franco-Belgian television series created by screenwriters Manon Dillys and Anthony Maugendre and directed by Frank Bellocq and Méliane Marcaggi, and broadcast in Belgium from October 3, 2024 on La Une and in France from October 21, 2024 on TF1.
Jaligny-sur-Besbre is a commune located in the Allier department, in the Auvergne-Rhône-Alpes region. Formerly called Jaligny, it took its current name on November 20, 1967.

Medardus or Medard (French: Médard or Méard) (ca. 456–545) was the Bishop of Noyon. He moved the seat of the diocese from Vermand to Noviomagus Veromanduorum (modern Noyon) in northern France. Medardus was one of the most honored bishops of his time, often depicted laughing, with his mouth wide open, and therefore he was invoked against toothache.

input_name: Eglise Catholique Russe de la Très-Sainte Trinité
wiki_name: Église catholique russe de la Très-Sainte-Trinité de Paris
wiki_description: The Russian Catholic Church of the Most Holy Trinity of Paris (Приxoд Пресвятой Троицы) is a Catholic church, belonging to the Greco-Russian branch, of the Byzantine rite officiated in Slavonic and dedicated to the Holy Trinity. It is located at 39 rue François-Gérard, in Paris, in the 16th arrondissement.

Louis His reign extended from May 14, 1643 - under the regency of his mother Anne of Austria until September 7, 1651 - until his death in 1715. His reign of 72 years was one of the longest in the history of Europe and the longest in the history of France.

input_name: Jardin de la Poterne des Peupliers
wiki_description: The Jardin de la Poterne-des-Peupliers is a green space in the 13th arrondissement of Paris, France, which includes a section of the Petite Ceinture.
Allée des Fortifications is a road located in the 16th arrondissement of Paris, France.

The G-spot or Gräfenberg point (names given in homage to Ernst Gräfenberg, German gynecologist) is a hypothetical erogenous zone of the anterior wall of the vagina, bulbous in shape, measuring less than a centimeter in diameter, and which, through stimulation, increases its size.

The 18th arrondissement of Paris is one of the twenty arrondissements of Paris. Located on the right bank of the Seine, it includes part of the former communes of Montmartre and de la Chapelle, attached to Paris in 1860. It is the third arrondissement of the city in terms of population, after the 15th arrondissement and the 20th arrondissement. The eastern half borders Saint-Denis and Aubervilliers (Goutte-d'Or district; La Chapelle district) while the western half borders Saint-Ouen-sur-Seine (Grandes-Carrières district; Clignancourt district). The northern limit of the district is made up of the ring road, between the Porte de Saint-Ouen and the Porte d'Aubervilliers. Its other limits are formed to the west by the 17th arrondissement of Paris, to the south by the 9th and 10th arrondissements and to the east by the 19th arrondissement.

The René-Dumont tropical agronomy garden is a green space in Paris, France. Located at the eastern end of the Bois de Vincennes. It occupies the site of the former colonial trial garden, created at the end of the 19th century to increase agricultural production in the French colonies.

wiki_name: Musée national des Arts et Traditions Populaires
